WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.92
This is Jocko podcast number 358 with Dave Burke and me,

2
00:00:03.92 --> 00:00:04.80
Jocko Willink.

3
00:00:04.80 --> 00:00:05.76
Good evening, Dave.

4
00:00:05.76 --> 00:00:06.24
Good evening.

5
00:00:08.40 --> 00:00:12.72
It is with deep personal concern that I officially inform

6
00:00:12.72 --> 00:00:17.20
you that your son, first Lieutenant Leon F. Ellis, Jr.

7
00:00:18.72 --> 00:00:24.64
is reported missing in North Vietnam on 7 November 1967.

8
00:00:24.64 --> 00:00:31.68
He was a pilot on an F-4C aircraft on an operational mission.

9
00:00:32.96 --> 00:00:35.92
His aircraft was last seen to roll in on target.

10
00:00:36.88 --> 00:00:40.08
Shortly thereafter, a large fireball was seen,

11
00:00:40.08 --> 00:00:42.72
where his aircraft previously was located.

12
00:00:44.08 --> 00:00:46.96
The fireball descended to the ground and impacted.

13
00:00:48.48 --> 00:00:52.32
The crew was not seen to bail out, but however,

14
00:00:52.32 --> 00:00:56.80
voice contact was established with your son on ground.

15
00:00:58.16 --> 00:01:00.48
Rescue operations are in progress.

16
00:01:01.68 --> 00:01:04.56
Lieutenant Ellis may have been captured.

17
00:01:06.24 --> 00:01:11.44
For his welfare, it is recommended that in reply to questions from other

18
00:01:11.44 --> 00:01:19.12
than your immediate family, you give only his name, grade, serial number, and date of birth.

19
00:01:19.12 --> 00:01:25.36
If this is the information he must provide if captured, please be assured when new

20
00:01:25.36 --> 00:01:29.12
information is received, it will be furnished to you immediately.

21
00:01:29.12 --> 00:01:36.72
A representative from Dobbins Air Force Base will contact you within 48 hours to assist

22
00:01:36.72 --> 00:01:38.40
in any way possible.

23
00:01:39.60 --> 00:01:44.88
If you have any questions you may call my personal representative,

24
00:01:44.88 --> 00:01:53.36
please accept my sympathy during this period of anxiety.

25
00:01:56.48 --> 00:02:03.20
Brigadier General George E. McCord, Military Personnel Center, Headquarters, United States Air Force.

26
00:02:03.20 --> 00:02:16.64
And that was the telegram received by Leon and Moline Ellis, parents of First Lieutenant Leon Ellis Jr.

27
00:02:18.80 --> 00:02:24.24
Probably one of the most terrifying things a parent could ever hear about their child.

28
00:02:24.24 --> 00:02:35.44
But the good news is Leon Ellis Jr. or Lee Ellis did survive being shot down.

29
00:02:35.44 --> 00:02:37.28
The bad news is he was captured.

30
00:02:38.56 --> 00:02:46.96
He was captured by the North Vietnamese and ended up spending five and a half years as a prisoner of war.

31
00:02:49.52 --> 00:02:53.12
But the good news is he did survive that.

32
00:02:53.12 --> 00:02:59.84
He went on to become a colonel in the Air Force and after that a speaker, a leadership consultant,

33
00:02:59.84 --> 00:03:00.56
and an author.

34
00:03:01.68 --> 00:03:11.68
He's written three books, Leading with Honor, another book called Engage with Honor, and a fourth coming book called Captured by Love.

35
00:03:11.68 --> 00:03:23.68
And it is a distinct privilege and an honor to have Lee Ellis with us here tonight to discuss his experiences and his lessons learned.

36
00:03:24.24 --> 00:03:26.72
Sir, thank you for joining us.

37
00:03:27.20 --> 00:03:28.000
Thank you, Jaco.

38
00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.04
It's great to be with you.

39
00:03:29.60 --> 00:03:35.36
I really enjoyed your book, your in life, Babin's book, leadership book, certificate.

40
00:03:37.20 --> 00:03:38.32
I can tell you the name of it.

41
00:03:38.32 --> 00:03:40.08
I've written a bunch of them, but it's all good.

42
00:03:40.08 --> 00:03:44.88
But it was so good and I quoted it in several places in my book.

43
00:03:44.88 --> 00:03:49.04
So thank you for what you've done and are doing and it's a pleasure to be with you.

44
00:03:49.04 --> 00:03:49.68
I'm excited.

45
00:03:50.24 --> 00:03:51.92
Yeah, I appreciate it for sure.

46
00:03:51.92 --> 00:04:02.16
And I mean, reading your books and having had a couple other POWs from Vietnam on this podcast.

47
00:04:02.16 --> 00:04:06.16
We had William Reeder, who was a helicopter pilot, was shot down.

48
00:04:06.16 --> 00:04:20.16
He was shot down in South Vietnam, so he made the treacherous journey, months long journey through the jungle, staying in the jungle camps, which were, you know, by his account, the absolute horror.

49
00:04:20.16 --> 00:04:22.72
And then, of course, we've had Charlie Plum on as well.

50
00:04:22.72 --> 00:04:24.72
And I know you know him.

51
00:04:24.72 --> 00:04:28.16
So honor to have you here share your experiences.

52
00:04:28.16 --> 00:04:35.20
The perspective that you all bring to leadership and to life is just unbelievable.

53
00:04:35.20 --> 00:04:37.20
And it's something very powerful.

54
00:04:37.20 --> 00:04:49.20
I know as I read through what you all experienced, it's impossible not to try and take some lessons from that and improve the way I live as a human being.

55
00:04:49.20 --> 00:04:59.20
But with that, let's, before we jump into your time in Vietnam, let's start off in the beginning and how you grew up.

56
00:04:59.20 --> 00:05:01.20
So you were born in Georgia, right?

57
00:05:01.20 --> 00:05:03.20
Yes.

58
00:05:03.20 --> 00:05:11.20
I was born down in South Georgia, but when I was about two years old, my parents moved back to North Georgia because my grandmother had cancer.

59
00:05:11.20 --> 00:05:15.20
And we wanted to live near my mother's parents on the farm.

60
00:05:15.20 --> 00:05:23.20
And we lived in a four-bedroom house there on the farm, not a four-bedroom.

61
00:05:23.20 --> 00:05:25.20
Two bedrooms, a living room, and a kitchen.

62
00:05:25.20 --> 00:05:27.20
That was it.

63
00:05:27.20 --> 00:05:33.20
Back in, that was back in the 40s, my grandmother died, and then we moved in with my grandfather on that farm.

64
00:05:33.20 --> 00:05:39.20
So I grew up in the real days of farming.

65
00:05:39.20 --> 00:05:43.20
We went, by the way, we went barefooted from May until October.

66
00:05:43.20 --> 00:05:45.20
That was a thing we were proud of.

67
00:05:45.20 --> 00:05:47.20
We wanted to get those shoes off and go barefooted.

68
00:05:47.20 --> 00:05:53.20
Didn't wear a shirt much in the summertime and worked on the farm.

69
00:05:53.20 --> 00:05:57.20
Looking back, it was good that we had that responsibility.

70
00:05:57.20 --> 00:06:03.20
My dad was not a farmer, but he learned to do some and work some.

71
00:06:03.20 --> 00:06:05.20
But my brother and I worked a lot there on the farm.

72
00:06:05.20 --> 00:06:13.20
My mother was a wonderful cook, and we had this huge garden, and we would grow an acre of garden stuff.

73
00:06:13.20 --> 00:06:19.20
So my mother would can a hundred quarts of beans every summer.

74
00:06:19.20 --> 00:06:23.20
And corn and peas and butter beans and all this stuff.

75
00:06:23.20 --> 00:06:29.20
Well, my brother and I did a lot of that work, and we would sit on the front porch in the swing,

76
00:06:29.20 --> 00:06:35.20
shelling butter beans or string and beans at night, listen to the Atlanta crackers,

77
00:06:35.20 --> 00:06:39.20
which was like a double-A baseball team before it became the Atlanta Braves.

78
00:06:39.20 --> 00:06:41.20
And that was life, you know.

79
00:06:41.20 --> 00:06:43.20
It was a good life and hard work.

80
00:06:43.20 --> 00:06:48.20
My brother milked a cow because my dad went to work in town.

81
00:06:48.20 --> 00:06:50.20
My brother would milk the cow in the morning and evening.

82
00:06:50.20 --> 00:06:53.20
That was good because I didn't have the same grip he did.

83
00:06:53.20 --> 00:06:55.20
He was bigger than me and older.

84
00:06:55.20 --> 00:07:00.20
But I fed the hogs, fed the chickens, chopped the wood and brought in the coals every day.

85
00:07:00.20 --> 00:07:04.20
So, you know, this was the good thing was we learned about responsibility.

86
00:07:04.20 --> 00:07:06.20
We learned about being in the cold.

87
00:07:06.20 --> 00:07:10.20
We drove cars that sometimes the batteries were dead and you had to push them off.

88
00:07:10.20 --> 00:07:12.20
They were all straight shifts.

89
00:07:12.20 --> 00:07:17.20
So it was an era when we just, as young kids on the farm, we had a lot of responsibility.

90
00:07:17.20 --> 00:07:25.20
But out there on that farm, during the Korean War, so which was 1951 to 53 or 54 timeframe,

91
00:07:25.20 --> 00:07:31.20
I was born in 43, so I was like eight, nine, ten years old.

92
00:07:31.20 --> 00:07:40.20
And I'd be out there on the farm working and I'd keep looking up because overhead with these huge formations of airplanes

93
00:07:40.20 --> 00:07:45.20
going off to war or going off to prepare people or drop, you know, paratroopers or whatever.

94
00:07:45.20 --> 00:07:47.20
And I'd look up at those airplanes.

95
00:07:47.20 --> 00:07:48.20
Oh, wow.

96
00:07:48.20 --> 00:07:54.20
And all of that because when I was five, my parents took me to Athens, Georgia, which is 10 miles away,

97
00:07:54.20 --> 00:07:57.20
what the University of Georgia Bulldogs are, by the way.

98
00:07:57.20 --> 00:08:04.20
And in the park, the Veterans Park in Athens, Georgia, there was a World War II fighter plane.

99
00:08:04.20 --> 00:08:10.20
And I climbed up on that wing and it was like at age five or six, I said, this is me.

100
00:08:10.20 --> 00:08:13.20
This is what I'm going to do.

101
00:08:13.20 --> 00:08:17.20
Well, now, I was also big into sports.

102
00:08:17.20 --> 00:08:22.20
My brother, my mother's brother had played football at the University of Georgia in 1928, 29.

103
00:08:22.20 --> 00:08:30.20
He became a doctor and his two sons played on scholarship at the University of Georgia in 50, 51, 52.

104
00:08:30.20 --> 00:08:35.20
So we would go down and watch the University of Georgia football practice over on Ag Hill there.

105
00:08:35.20 --> 00:08:41.20
So I got this in my mind and I wanted to be a quarterback at the University of Georgia.

106
00:08:41.20 --> 00:08:49.20
So I was a quarterback in high school and I was above average, but I wasn't the fastest guy on the team.

107
00:08:49.20 --> 00:08:55.20
In my senior year in high school, I only weighed 155 and they did not recruit me, which I didn't expect them to.

108
00:08:55.20 --> 00:09:01.20
So I went on to the University of Georgia when I finished high school and got in Air Force ROTC.

109
00:09:01.20 --> 00:09:04.20
And then I knew that was what I wanted to do.

110
00:09:04.20 --> 00:09:06.20
So what year is that that you go to college?

111
00:09:06.20 --> 00:09:09.20
I graduated high school in 1961.

112
00:09:09.20 --> 00:09:15.20
I went to college then and graduated in four years in 1965.

113
00:09:15.20 --> 00:09:24.20
Now, I was probably the worst student ever to graduate in four years because I had never really learned to study.

114
00:09:24.20 --> 00:09:30.20
I was kind of ADD and focused on whatever and I had to work to pay my college tuition and all that.

115
00:09:30.20 --> 00:09:36.20
I didn't have any money, so I worked and lived at home after my first semester there.

116
00:09:36.20 --> 00:09:40.20
I lived on campus just because I saved up money and wanted to do it.

117
00:09:40.20 --> 00:09:52.20
But in ROTC, I graduated as a distinguished graduate and went to flight school with the Academy Class A class of flight school.

118
00:09:52.20 --> 00:09:54.20
Was it was it hard to get into flight school?

119
00:09:54.20 --> 00:09:57.20
Not for me.

120
00:09:57.20 --> 00:10:04.20
I passed the exam and the written exams and I got my pilot's license my senior year in college.

121
00:10:04.20 --> 00:10:12.20
The Air Force had a flight indoctrination program where they kind of screened you out and I sailed through that and went right to flight school.

122
00:10:12.20 --> 00:10:22.20
I had always been driving. I started driving cars when I was 11, tractors when I was 12, and I could drive them by myself.

123
00:10:22.20 --> 00:10:26.20
I mean, they would let me go with responsibility to go drive them.

124
00:10:26.20 --> 00:10:31.20
I chauffeured for my grandfather when I was 12 and 13.

125
00:10:31.20 --> 00:10:40.20
I'd always been very confident about operating machinery and taking risks and being able to go right to the edge but not go over it.

126
00:10:40.20 --> 00:10:45.20
And so it just was a natural place to be.

127
00:10:45.20 --> 00:10:53.20
And when they told me that I passed the physical to be a pilot after my sophomore year, I was just thrilled.

128
00:10:53.20 --> 00:10:55.20
And I went over and changed my major.

129
00:10:55.20 --> 00:11:03.20
I was in pre-med and because my uncle had been a doctor and I wasn't going to get into medical school with my grades because I didn't study.

130
00:11:03.20 --> 00:11:09.20
I went over and changed my major to history and sailed right on through in four years and off to flight school.

131
00:11:09.20 --> 00:11:15.20
And flight school for me, I had a check every month.

132
00:11:15.20 --> 00:11:17.20
I bought myself a new car.

133
00:11:17.20 --> 00:11:19.20
What kind of car was it?

134
00:11:19.20 --> 00:11:23.20
Well, I was going to get either a school to get a GTO.

135
00:11:23.20 --> 00:11:29.20
They'd only come out with GTOs in 64 and this was summer of 1965.

136
00:11:29.20 --> 00:11:38.20
The problem was the GTO was bucket seats and I wanted a bent seat because back then I wanted my honey to be sitting like real close.

137
00:11:38.20 --> 00:11:41.20
And I said, I'm going to buy one of those stupid GTOs.

138
00:11:41.20 --> 00:11:42.20
I love GTO.

139
00:11:42.20 --> 00:11:51.20
So I bought the Cutlass Supreme which is exactly like the GTO except a little bit smaller engine and had a bent seat.

140
00:11:51.20 --> 00:11:54.20
And I bought wire wheels on it to be cool.

141
00:11:54.20 --> 00:12:01.20
And my roommate bought a, his dad was a Ford dealer and he got a Mustang.

142
00:12:01.20 --> 00:12:04.20
So my roommate in flight school.

143
00:12:04.20 --> 00:12:10.20
So we were cool and the Beldost State College was right down there in Beldost, 11 miles away.

144
00:12:10.20 --> 00:12:13.20
We could just roll in there.

145
00:12:13.20 --> 00:12:18.20
We'd go to the freshman dorm and say, well, who's in there?

146
00:12:18.20 --> 00:12:24.20
And they had to sign out. We'd say, well, Janie and so and so will bring them down here and let us meet them.

147
00:12:24.20 --> 00:12:25.20
And they would.

148
00:12:25.20 --> 00:12:26.20
We liked them.

149
00:12:26.20 --> 00:12:28.20
We'd take them to the, let's go to the clubs.

150
00:12:28.20 --> 00:12:33.20
So I did not study very hard in UPT.

151
00:12:33.20 --> 00:12:35.20
And to me, UPT, I had a check.

152
00:12:35.20 --> 00:12:36.20
I had a car.

153
00:12:36.20 --> 00:12:43.20
There's girls nearby and I was living the life that I wanted to live in college but also doing flight school.

154
00:12:43.20 --> 00:12:44.20
Wait, what's UPT?

155
00:12:44.20 --> 00:12:45.20
Undergraduate pilot training.

156
00:12:45.20 --> 00:12:46.20
Okay.

157
00:12:46.20 --> 00:12:51.20
So is that before you go to, before you go, before you graduate from college?

158
00:12:51.20 --> 00:12:53.20
No, this is right after I graduated.

159
00:12:53.20 --> 00:12:55.20
Okay. So you graduate, you get commissioned.

160
00:12:55.20 --> 00:13:00.20
Three days later, I was in flight school in Beldost, Georgia at Moody Air Force.

161
00:13:00.20 --> 00:13:02.20
And this is 1965, right?

162
00:13:02.20 --> 00:13:03.20
Yes.

163
00:13:03.20 --> 00:13:04.20
What are you hearing about Vietnam?

164
00:13:04.20 --> 00:13:05.20
How much is that on the radar right now?

165
00:13:05.20 --> 00:13:08.20
It's starting to jump, jump up and you, there's some debates.

166
00:13:08.20 --> 00:13:09.20
You see them.

167
00:13:09.20 --> 00:13:14.20
If you watch TV, there'll be some debates on there and Secretary Russ could be on there.

168
00:13:14.20 --> 00:13:16.20
They'll be talking about it.

169
00:13:16.20 --> 00:13:30.20
And we'd see a lot of Army helicopters would come through and pass refuel and there in Moody and going, you know, this was when the Army, Airborne, an Army, whatever the helicopter groups were called, really got going.

170
00:13:30.20 --> 00:13:31.20
Air cab.

171
00:13:31.20 --> 00:13:32.20
Air cab got going.

172
00:13:32.20 --> 00:13:33.20
That's right.

173
00:13:33.20 --> 00:13:34.20
And they would come through.

174
00:13:34.20 --> 00:13:40.20
But in flight school, we didn't have any instructor pilots that had already been on a tour.

175
00:13:40.20 --> 00:13:50.20
And then as I was in a T-38, which was the second stage, the advanced flights, part of flight school, there was a major came in, a single guy who was a major.

176
00:13:50.20 --> 00:14:02.20
And he'd just come back from a tour in Vietnam as a, as a, the, what's the Navy prop airplane that's there for us had one too.

177
00:14:02.20 --> 00:14:03.20
A1.

178
00:14:03.20 --> 00:14:04.20
A1 Sky Raider.

179
00:14:04.20 --> 00:14:05.20
He'd been an A1 Sky Raider pilot.

180
00:14:05.20 --> 00:14:11.20
He's a fighter pilot, but he'd been an A1 pilot for a tour over there and he told us about it.

181
00:14:11.20 --> 00:14:16.20
And he went cross country with us and he was, he was a fun, a really great leader and a great guy.

182
00:14:16.20 --> 00:14:20.20
So he was the first combat veteran we'd ever met.

183
00:14:20.20 --> 00:14:21.20
And he was single.

184
00:14:21.20 --> 00:14:25.20
So that was fun.

185
00:14:25.20 --> 00:14:28.20
What's the, what's the training aircraft, the T-38?

186
00:14:28.20 --> 00:14:29.20
The T-38.

187
00:14:29.20 --> 00:14:31.20
Is that the same one you use now, Dave?

188
00:14:31.20 --> 00:14:32.20
It's the Air Force still using it.

189
00:14:32.20 --> 00:14:33.20
Yeah.

190
00:14:33.20 --> 00:14:35.20
They've been using it 60 years or so.

191
00:14:35.20 --> 00:14:39.20
It had just come out into the Air Force in 63, 64.

192
00:14:39.20 --> 00:14:45.20
And so it's a supersonic 20-inch and afterburner two-seater.

193
00:14:45.20 --> 00:14:48.20
The fighter version of it was the F-5.

194
00:14:48.20 --> 00:14:49.20
Got it.

195
00:14:49.20 --> 00:14:51.20
But, you know, it would go supersonic.

196
00:14:51.20 --> 00:14:54.20
It would, it would climb great.

197
00:14:54.20 --> 00:14:56.20
It was a great airplane for us to fly.

198
00:14:56.20 --> 00:15:01.20
It flew, it flew faster on final than most of the airplanes do now, you know.

199
00:15:01.20 --> 00:15:05.20
Now, are you competing for that fighter pilot slot?

200
00:15:05.20 --> 00:15:09.20
Yes, but they were going to be plentiful.

201
00:15:09.20 --> 00:15:19.20
I was in, I was in the top 10% of my class until on my contact evaluation of the T-38.

202
00:15:19.20 --> 00:15:25.20
My instructor had told me, well, on the single-engine landing, don't worry too much about your airspeed.

203
00:15:25.20 --> 00:15:30.20
Well, on my check ride, my airspeed was about 10 or 12 knots high and I got downgraded.

204
00:15:30.20 --> 00:15:39.20
And that took me from like third or fourth in my class down to about the 50%ile in my class.

205
00:15:39.20 --> 00:15:41.20
And it just couldn't get back up.

206
00:15:41.20 --> 00:15:44.20
There wasn't enough more check rides to get much higher back up.

207
00:15:44.20 --> 00:15:47.20
So I was probably in the top 40%.

208
00:15:47.20 --> 00:15:50.20
But technically in my mind, I knew where I was.

209
00:15:50.20 --> 00:15:52.20
I should have been up there in the 10%.

210
00:15:52.20 --> 00:15:59.20
But the, in my class, which was 67A, it was in 1966.

211
00:15:59.20 --> 00:16:03.20
But the physical year, we graduated in August 1966.

212
00:16:03.20 --> 00:16:16.20
Across eight training bases, there were 500, I'm sorry, there were over 800 pilots being trained that whole year.

213
00:16:16.20 --> 00:16:20.20
And over 500 of us got F-4 backseat.

214
00:16:20.20 --> 00:16:22.20
They were putting pilots in the backseat.

215
00:16:22.20 --> 00:16:24.20
Now, the Navy didn't put pilots in the backseat.

216
00:16:24.20 --> 00:16:26.20
They put reels.

217
00:16:26.20 --> 00:16:33.20
But the Air Force was trying to get, use money to get more pilots training.

218
00:16:33.20 --> 00:16:34.20
Okay.

219
00:16:34.20 --> 00:16:40.20
So they said to Congress or somebody, hey, we need more pilots because they put in pilots in the backseat.

220
00:16:40.20 --> 00:16:43.20
And so we had to go over there first tour in the backseat.

221
00:16:43.20 --> 00:16:51.20
So, and as I was going through my combat training, there were some of the front seaters that I knew I was a lot better pilot than they were.

222
00:16:51.20 --> 00:16:53.20
But I helped them look good.

223
00:16:53.20 --> 00:16:56.20
Most of them were good, but not all of them.

224
00:16:56.20 --> 00:17:02.20
So you get done with that, you get done with the T-38 and then it's into, then you get assigned the Phantom.

225
00:17:02.20 --> 00:17:03.20
Yes.

226
00:17:03.20 --> 00:17:07.20
And how, but were you assigned the backseat for the Phantom?

227
00:17:07.20 --> 00:17:08.20
Yes.

228
00:17:08.20 --> 00:17:11.20
And then were you mad about that?

229
00:17:11.20 --> 00:17:16.20
Well, I was, but there were only three other single seat fighters in my class.

230
00:17:16.20 --> 00:17:17.20
Okay.

231
00:17:17.20 --> 00:17:26.20
There were one guy got a 105 and one guy got a 102 and everybody else got backseat F4.

232
00:17:26.20 --> 00:17:29.20
So, but there was no choice.

233
00:17:29.20 --> 00:17:38.20
All of us, all my buddies and I went there and, you know, we were going to go do it and pay our dues and get out and go to the front seat or go to another airplane.

234
00:17:38.20 --> 00:17:40.20
So that was kind of a normal pattern.

235
00:17:40.20 --> 00:17:43.20
You'd go to the backseat for a tour and then you get, get into the front seat.

236
00:17:43.20 --> 00:17:57.20
I was actually, I didn't know this, but my buddy Lance Sideson, who went down two days after I did, metal of honor guy, we were, and I was starting, they were starting to fly us a little bit with some instructor pilots who were check pilots.

237
00:17:57.20 --> 00:18:01.20
And they didn't tell us this, but they were going to upgrade us to the front seat in combat.

238
00:18:01.20 --> 00:18:03.20
I found that after I came home.

239
00:18:03.20 --> 00:18:10.20
And I thought, that's not very wise to upgrade somebody to the front seat where you didn't even in the backseat, you didn't have a pickle button.

240
00:18:10.20 --> 00:18:14.20
You couldn't pickle the bombs and fire the gun in the backseat.

241
00:18:14.20 --> 00:18:17.20
You could fly the airplane to everything, but you couldn't pickle the.

242
00:18:17.20 --> 00:18:21.20
So you would need further training on that before you moved up there.

243
00:18:21.20 --> 00:18:27.20
The, the F4 Phantom is my favorite American bird.

244
00:18:27.20 --> 00:18:32.20
That thing was just like a modern masterpiece at the time, right?

245
00:18:32.20 --> 00:18:34.20
Yes, it was.

246
00:18:34.20 --> 00:18:44.20
It was a lot of power and it wasn't the sharpest turning one, but it would turn pretty, pretty, pretty dog on good.

247
00:18:44.20 --> 00:18:48.20
It would pull Gs well and it had a lot of power and it could carry a lot of stuff.

248
00:18:48.20 --> 00:18:53.20
The problem was it was built as a Navy long range interceptor.

249
00:18:53.20 --> 00:18:54.20
Okay.

250
00:18:54.20 --> 00:18:56.20
So they didn't have a gun built into it.

251
00:18:56.20 --> 00:18:58.20
Just had it with missiles.

252
00:18:58.20 --> 00:19:01.20
Well, the Air Force wanted it for more air to ground and air to air.

253
00:19:01.20 --> 00:19:11.20
So we actually started carrying a pod gun, a 20 millimeter pod gun underneath in the center station while I was there.

254
00:19:11.20 --> 00:19:13.20
And we did quite a bit of that.

255
00:19:13.20 --> 00:19:18.20
It was the same gun that they later built into the airplane in the F4E.

256
00:19:18.20 --> 00:19:21.20
And the, now the ATN now has a 40 millimeter gun.

257
00:19:21.20 --> 00:19:25.20
They built an airplane around the gun, but yeah.

258
00:19:25.20 --> 00:19:30.20
So then when, when you get done with that training, how, how long is it before you go to Vietnam?

259
00:19:30.20 --> 00:19:40.20
Normally the, the replacement training unit, which would be like the RAG and the Navy, the RTU and the Air Force, we went to, I went to George Air Force Base.

260
00:19:40.20 --> 00:19:48.20
There were three different bases that were doing it in the high desert right near where Top Gun works out and was filmed there in the high desert.

261
00:19:48.20 --> 00:19:53.20
And we go there and we do air to ground, air to air refueling and that sort of thing.

262
00:19:53.20 --> 00:19:55.20
And then we deployed straight to war.

263
00:19:55.20 --> 00:20:06.20
The order said, F4, F4 Phantom pipeline Southeast Asia pipeline meant as quick as he gets combat trained, he's going to go to Southeast Asia.

264
00:20:06.20 --> 00:20:09.20
And so now it's 1967.

265
00:20:09.20 --> 00:20:10.20
Yes.

266
00:20:10.20 --> 00:20:13.20
And so now Vietnam is pretty much in full swing.

267
00:20:13.20 --> 00:20:14.20
Yes.

268
00:20:14.20 --> 00:20:23.20
And how's that sit with you, with your teammates, you guys just all like that's your goal is to get to Vietnam and fly in.

269
00:20:23.20 --> 00:20:25.20
And I think most of us were, that's where we're going to go.

270
00:20:25.20 --> 00:20:30.20
And they changed our assignment two, three times because the weather over there and different things.

271
00:20:30.20 --> 00:20:37.20
So one time they told us we were going to go to Japan to Masawa and stay there and we go TDY to the war.

272
00:20:37.20 --> 00:20:43.20
Well, the wives and kids were getting shots and everything getting ready to go overseas to Japan.

273
00:20:43.20 --> 00:20:45.20
And I thought, well, it'll be okay.

274
00:20:45.20 --> 00:20:47.20
We're going to take F4Es over to Japan.

275
00:20:47.20 --> 00:20:50.20
And then all of a sudden about two weeks later they said, that's been canceled.

276
00:20:50.20 --> 00:20:52.20
We're back to the original.

277
00:20:52.20 --> 00:20:54.20
And so you're going to go straight to the war.

278
00:20:54.20 --> 00:21:02.20
So the main thing we did though was we got, we'd already had survival training before I went to George to get the combat training.

279
00:21:02.20 --> 00:21:05.20
And so now we go to water survival because we had a little bit of time.

280
00:21:05.20 --> 00:21:07.20
They said, you're not going to go to July.

281
00:21:07.20 --> 00:21:13.20
So I went to water survival and then departed the states on about 30 or 30 June or so.

282
00:21:13.20 --> 00:21:19.20
Headed, went to the Philippines through jungle survival school about a week there in the world.

283
00:21:19.20 --> 00:21:20.20
What year is this?

284
00:21:20.20 --> 00:21:21.20
1967.

285
00:21:21.20 --> 00:21:22.20
Okay.

286
00:21:22.20 --> 00:21:36.20
And then straight from there to Da Nang, which was in the northern part of South Vietnam, about 70 miles south of the DMC that separated North Vietnam from South Vietnam.

287
00:21:36.20 --> 00:21:39.20
And so there's, that's where you end up flying out of.

288
00:21:39.20 --> 00:21:40.20
That's where your, your base is.

289
00:21:40.20 --> 00:21:41.20
Yes.

290
00:21:41.20 --> 00:21:42.20
You end up flying out of Da Nang.

291
00:21:42.20 --> 00:21:43.20
Yes.

292
00:21:43.20 --> 00:21:46.20
And we flew a lot of combat stories over the north.

293
00:21:46.20 --> 00:21:47.20
Those were our counters.

294
00:21:47.20 --> 00:21:50.20
If you got a hundred stories over the north, you could go home.

295
00:21:50.20 --> 00:21:55.20
If you only flew over South Vietnam, you had to fly for a year before you go back home.

296
00:21:55.20 --> 00:22:13.20
So whenever we could convert a mission in Laos or South Vietnam, get something done and then have a little bit of ammo left, we'd go over to north Vietnam and work with the Ford air controller there, the Missy Facts, and get that counter in.

297
00:22:13.20 --> 00:22:18.20
What was the, what was the main mission that you were getting tasked with doing?

298
00:22:18.20 --> 00:22:20.20
It was, there were two missions.

299
00:22:20.20 --> 00:22:29.20
One was close air support for combat troops in I Corps, which was the northern part of South Vietnam in support of the Marines and the army.

300
00:22:29.20 --> 00:22:30.20
So we would do those.

301
00:22:30.20 --> 00:22:39.20
We would sit alert sometimes for that and we'd get scrambled and go out when they got, are about to get overrun or something, getting attacked and go out and do close air support.

302
00:22:39.20 --> 00:22:40.20
And that was a lot of fun.

303
00:22:40.20 --> 00:22:58.20
But most of our missions, I had about 15 or 18 of those kind of missions, but most of the missions were road recce and bombing of trucks on the road, bombing out bridges, keep the roads bombed out.

304
00:22:58.20 --> 00:23:06.20
So they could not, the Ho Chi Minh Trail, to keep them from bringing truckloads of troops and war materials into South Vietnam.

305
00:23:06.20 --> 00:23:11.20
They would come down south, the Ho Chi Minh Trail, which ran parallel to the coastline.

306
00:23:11.20 --> 00:23:21.20
And then as they got to the DMZ, they would cut over into Laos and then go down through Laos and then cut back into South Vietnam.

307
00:23:21.20 --> 00:23:23.20
Because that was the safest way for them to travel.

308
00:23:23.20 --> 00:23:28.20
So that's why we flew into Laos was to blow up those bridges and roads.

309
00:23:28.20 --> 00:23:33.20
And if we could get a convoy of trucks, you know, we could wipe those out pretty quickly.

310
00:23:33.20 --> 00:23:36.20
And that's where that, so that was the main mission that you did?

311
00:23:36.20 --> 00:23:37.20
Yes, it was.

312
00:23:37.20 --> 00:23:48.20
We were flying mixed combat air patrol supporting the bombers, fighter bombers, up around Hanoi when I got there at Da Nang.

313
00:23:48.20 --> 00:24:04.20
Most of those, they were Da Nang and U-Bahn, F-4s were supporting the air support for the 105s, F-4s, F-4s that were flying combat attacks in the Hanoi area up in North Vietnam industrial complex.

314
00:24:04.20 --> 00:24:12.20
But about four or five weeks after I got to Da Nang, the whole policy changed.

315
00:24:12.20 --> 00:24:25.20
12th Air Force was in Saigon and we were part of 12th Air Force, I'm sorry, 7th Air Force, and 12th Air Force controlled Laos and I'm sorry, controlled Thailand.

316
00:24:25.20 --> 00:24:31.20
And that's where we had four main bases in Thailand who were flying missions out of.

317
00:24:31.20 --> 00:24:36.20
And a lot of them were going over North Vietnam into the Hanoi area.

318
00:24:36.20 --> 00:24:44.20
So we lost the bombing and the combat air patrol support, MiG-CAP, I guess you call it, MiG-CAP.

319
00:24:44.20 --> 00:24:52.20
We lost that about a month after I got there, so I did not get to go on the MiG patrol up around Hanoi.

320
00:24:52.20 --> 00:24:55.20
And I was very disappointed because that's what I'd always wanted to do.

321
00:24:55.20 --> 00:24:56.20
Was just dogfight.

322
00:24:56.20 --> 00:24:58.20
Yeah, dogfight.

323
00:24:58.20 --> 00:25:00.20
Just pull plane against plane.

324
00:25:00.20 --> 00:25:02.20
Did you ever see any MiGs?

325
00:25:02.20 --> 00:25:04.20
Not from the air.

326
00:25:04.20 --> 00:25:06.20
I've seen them on the ground.

327
00:25:06.20 --> 00:25:10.20
When I was in prison up there, I saw them a few times.

328
00:25:10.20 --> 00:25:14.20
Do you remember your very first mission that you flew?

329
00:25:14.20 --> 00:25:20.20
Was it, you know, for like guys going into ground combat, you kind of remember the first time you rolled outside the wire?

330
00:25:20.20 --> 00:25:25.20
Was your first mission, was it monumental in your brain or was it just like, oh, another day?

331
00:25:25.20 --> 00:25:29.20
It was just like going out to the range and bombing, really.

332
00:25:29.20 --> 00:25:31.20
It was kind of more like that.

333
00:25:31.20 --> 00:25:33.20
It seems like these...

334
00:25:33.20 --> 00:25:34.20
I got shot at.

335
00:25:34.20 --> 00:25:37.20
I'd say most of all the missions we got shot at.

336
00:25:37.20 --> 00:25:43.20
And we'd come home and have some bullet holes from ground fire, mostly.

337
00:25:43.20 --> 00:25:47.20
I never got hit by any real AAA, I don't think, up there.

338
00:25:47.20 --> 00:25:54.20
I didn't have any big holes blowing up my airplane, but it was common to have, you know, ground fire rifles.

339
00:25:54.20 --> 00:25:58.20
Did you feel like the threat when you were flying up there?

340
00:25:58.20 --> 00:26:01.20
What was the threat level that you felt?

341
00:26:01.20 --> 00:26:08.20
I know in the book you end up mentioning you had, I think, three of your friends had been shot down.

342
00:26:08.20 --> 00:26:14.20
Like, how often is that happening where guys are getting shot down and you're rolling up there?

343
00:26:14.20 --> 00:26:21.20
What's your impression, or did you have the typical young man's impression, which, hey, it's too bad it happened to someone else,

344
00:26:21.20 --> 00:26:23.20
but it sure is not going to happen to me. I'm too good.

345
00:26:23.20 --> 00:26:25.20
Well, it was kind of that.

346
00:26:25.20 --> 00:26:27.20
But it was sad, too.

347
00:26:27.20 --> 00:26:35.20
I'd lost two roommates before I was shot down and another one after I was shot down.

348
00:26:35.20 --> 00:26:40.20
But there were a lot of people shot down.

349
00:26:40.20 --> 00:26:46.20
The summer and going into the fall of 1967, it was a huge number of people shot down

350
00:26:46.20 --> 00:26:50.20
because our combat missions increased significantly

351
00:26:50.20 --> 00:26:57.20
and there, and aircraft artillery, surface air missiles increased significantly during that time.

352
00:26:57.20 --> 00:27:01.20
So it was pretty common for airplanes to be going down.

353
00:27:01.20 --> 00:27:10.20
Did you feel like the skill level that it takes to drop bombs back in your day?

354
00:27:10.20 --> 00:27:14.20
I mean, nowadays it's a computer that's doing it. The computer's doing all the work.

355
00:27:14.20 --> 00:27:19.20
And you're just inputting the numbers and it's going to put that bomb wherever you tell that bomb to go.

356
00:27:19.20 --> 00:27:22.20
Did you feel like you're getting better?

357
00:27:22.20 --> 00:27:25.20
Were some guys better than other guys?

358
00:27:25.20 --> 00:27:31.20
In the SEAL teams, which I was in, you got this guy over here, he's really good, long range shot with his rifle.

359
00:27:31.20 --> 00:27:34.20
He's going to be super accurate. This other guy maybe is not so great.

360
00:27:34.20 --> 00:27:40.20
Did you guys have that kind of pecking order in terms of, hey, Lee's getting sent out to get this bridge

361
00:27:40.20 --> 00:27:43.20
because we know he's good or hey, don't send Lee out to get that bridge.

362
00:27:43.20 --> 00:27:47.20
Maybe he's not the best of our guys. Did you guys have that kind of pecking order?

363
00:27:47.20 --> 00:27:56.20
Yes and no. The flight commanders were generally established fighter pilots at that time.

364
00:27:56.20 --> 00:28:01.20
And so they were usually the best in the squadron. So they were set an example.

365
00:28:01.20 --> 00:28:12.20
But at this time, because of the war in 1967, by the summer of 1967, all the fighter pilots have gone over and done their year

366
00:28:12.20 --> 00:28:19.20
and come home, not all, but many, the first big chunk of them. And they don't want to send them right back.

367
00:28:19.20 --> 00:28:28.20
So they brought in guys from B-52s, from C-130s to become F-4 front-seaters in fighter pilots.

368
00:28:28.20 --> 00:28:36.20
Well, us back-seaters who had just been flying the T-38, we knew that one of our jobs was to keep them safe

369
00:28:36.20 --> 00:28:38.20
and help them be fighter pilots.

370
00:28:38.20 --> 00:28:43.20
Seriously, I mean, they were good pilots, but they just hadn't been flying fighter airplanes.

371
00:28:43.20 --> 00:28:48.20
And they were a little bit more cautious and slower thinking, I think, sometimes.

372
00:28:48.20 --> 00:28:53.20
And so we were almost coaching. There were times I was coaching the guy in the front seat.

373
00:28:53.20 --> 00:28:57.20
Now, don't roll in yet. We're not close enough to roll in yet.

374
00:28:57.20 --> 00:29:11.20
So, you know, it's hard to say, but most of the time when I flew with the more senior guys and who experienced fighter pilots, they were really good.

375
00:29:11.20 --> 00:29:24.20
And what about like, so you deploy in 1967, you're over there, the political thing in America of, you know, the war protests, they weren't really strong in 1967.

376
00:29:24.20 --> 00:29:29.20
No, it wasn't going strong yet. It was just starting to roll in certain parts of the country.

377
00:29:29.20 --> 00:29:43.20
I think the thing for me, I realized very quickly, and most of the pilots realized very quickly, that we were not fighting this war in the right way.

378
00:29:43.20 --> 00:29:53.20
And you saw that even from your time, you're a first lieutenant. You've been in the Navy for, or sorry, you've been in the Air Force for a short period of time.

379
00:29:53.20 --> 00:30:01.20
And you're already seeing, as a first lieutenant on your first deployment, this maybe doesn't make the most sense.

380
00:30:01.20 --> 00:30:07.20
Yes, I did see that. I said, why don't you let me figure out how to pick the targets?

381
00:30:07.20 --> 00:30:09.20
I mean, I did. I wanted to say.

382
00:30:09.20 --> 00:30:12.20
The targets are getting picked by like Washington D.C. and stuff, right?

383
00:30:12.20 --> 00:30:15.20
Yes, yes, exactly. And I'd say, well, here's how we need to do this.

384
00:30:15.20 --> 00:30:25.20
We need to go up there and bomb out the roads, you know, just bomb them out in certain specific places intentionally, about an hour before dark.

385
00:30:25.20 --> 00:30:31.20
And then as quick as it gets dark, the trucks will back up and we'll go in and strafe them all and wipe them out.

386
00:30:31.20 --> 00:30:36.20
Well, that would took me about a month to figure that out.

387
00:30:36.20 --> 00:30:41.20
And sometimes we did that, and sometimes we didn't, but it wasn't part of the plan.

388
00:30:41.20 --> 00:30:47.20
There was no plan to do that. You had to fly authorities to some degree to when Saigon said fly them.

389
00:30:47.20 --> 00:30:53.20
And to a large degree up around Hanoi, you could only fly them when they told you to.

390
00:30:53.20 --> 00:30:56.20
And of course, the enemy knew exactly when we were coming.

391
00:30:56.20 --> 00:31:06.20
So it was just ridiculous that so many decisions about what to bomb and when to bomb it was made in Washington D.C. by civilians who knew nothing about warfare.

392
00:31:06.20 --> 00:31:10.20
And even you as a first lieutenant, you're what, 23 years old, 24 years old?

393
00:31:10.20 --> 00:31:13.20
I was 23 when I got there.

394
00:31:13.20 --> 00:31:18.20
23 years old, you're just driving around a muscle car in America as a knuckle draggler.

395
00:31:18.20 --> 00:31:23.20
And even you figured out, hey, you can't micromanage this thing from Washington D.C.

396
00:31:23.20 --> 00:31:29.20
Yes. And I was, it was kind of down. It was kind of a downer for me.

397
00:31:29.20 --> 00:31:34.20
It's like, why can't somebody stand up and fix this, you know?

398
00:31:34.20 --> 00:31:43.20
At this point, are you seeing the POWs, any of that propaganda stuff that would come out over the years?

399
00:31:43.20 --> 00:31:46.20
Are you already seeing that some of that stuff?

400
00:31:46.20 --> 00:31:48.20
You mean in our culture?

401
00:31:48.20 --> 00:31:51.20
Yeah. So, so in other words, you're there, you're flying.

402
00:31:51.20 --> 00:31:58.20
At this point, obviously pilots had been shot down, pilots had been captured, soldiers, sailors had been captured.

403
00:31:58.20 --> 00:32:04.20
And that propaganda, you know, as POWs, is it not really out in 1967 yet?

404
00:32:04.20 --> 00:32:05.20
No.

405
00:32:05.20 --> 00:32:09.20
They weren't really pushing that hard, the Vietnamese to get that propaganda out.

406
00:32:09.20 --> 00:32:13.20
No, we had not, I had not heard any propaganda from POW camps.

407
00:32:13.20 --> 00:32:16.20
I didn't know anything about the POW camps of what was happening.

408
00:32:16.20 --> 00:32:21.20
I'm sure some folks did, but I knew some of my buddies had been captured,

409
00:32:21.20 --> 00:32:27.20
but I did not know what was happening there other than it was a, they were probably prisoners.

410
00:32:27.20 --> 00:32:34.20
So how many, how long had you been there before you ended up getting shot down?

411
00:32:34.20 --> 00:32:41.20
Well, I got there around the 3rd of July and I was shot down to 7th of November.

412
00:32:41.20 --> 00:32:51.20
And at that point, I had 53 missions over North Vietnam and another, I don't know, 15 or 16 or so over South Vietnam and Laos.

413
00:32:51.20 --> 00:32:57.20
All right, well, probably a good time for me to pick up this book.

414
00:32:57.20 --> 00:33:02.20
The book is called Leading with Honor Leadership Lessons from the Hulley Hilton.

415
00:33:02.20 --> 00:33:04.20
This is just out of the gate.

416
00:33:04.20 --> 00:33:07.20
We're starting it off from the book.

417
00:33:07.20 --> 00:33:17.20
It says this November 7th, 1967, four o'clock p.m. Captain Ken Fisher and I rolled into a dive bomb pass in our F4C Phantom jet.

418
00:33:17.20 --> 00:33:28.20
As we swoop downward, our bird with turned up wing tips, elevated tail and deafening roar must have resembled a high-tech version of a prehistoric pterodactyl.

419
00:33:28.20 --> 00:33:34.20
Tracers from the North Vietnamese anti-aircraft artillery flashed by our canopy like giant Roman candles,

420
00:33:34.20 --> 00:33:39.20
their explosions encircling us with ominous puffs of gray and black smoke,

421
00:33:39.20 --> 00:33:45.20
each representing hundreds of shards of shrapnel designed to mortally wound our beautiful beast.

422
00:33:45.20 --> 00:33:49.20
As our jet plunged toward the artillery positions at 500 miles an hour,

423
00:33:49.20 --> 00:33:55.20
the earth enlarged in our windscreen as if we were adjusting the zoom on a telephoto lens.

424
00:33:55.20 --> 00:34:01.20
It was eyeball to eyeball stare down with the enemy, with each side expecting the other to die.

425
00:34:01.20 --> 00:34:05.20
When you face enemy fire, you are at the point of the sword.

