825
01:09:42.20 --> 01:09:58.20
At Madman's command, guards had tied his arms behind his back, tossed a rope over a high beam and pulled Ken's arms up behind, lifting him until he was suspended with the weight of his body pulling and tearing at the muscles, ligaments and nerves in his shoulders.

826
01:09:58.20 --> 01:10:12.20
A star collegiate wrestler at New York State High School and New York State High School champion, Ken was mentally and physically one of the toughest men I'd ever known, but eventually the pain transformed him into a screaming idiot.

827
01:10:12.20 --> 01:10:18.20
As we all learned to do so, he had to fall back to the second line of resistance.

828
01:10:18.20 --> 01:10:28.20
At times some POWs prayed for death as a relief, but the V, who were experts at torture, rarely obliged.

829
01:10:28.20 --> 01:10:40.20
Upon hearing Ken's story, I felt embarrassed and immature. He had suffered so much trying to follow the strict letter of the code while I had given in after threats and a rifle jab to the head.

830
01:10:40.20 --> 01:10:52.20
When I shared my interrogation encounter with him, he said with sincere kindness, you did the best you could under the circumstances. We ended up at the same place giving them something that was nothing.

831
01:10:52.20 --> 01:11:03.20
That experience gave me a glimpse of the character of this man who would be a cellmate and inspirational leader for the next five years.

832
01:11:03.20 --> 01:11:14.20
That little piece of leadership right there, here's this guy that withstood the description, horrible torture.

833
01:11:14.20 --> 01:11:24.20
You tell him, hey, they put a gun in my head and I told him some information. He said, yeah, you did the best you could.

834
01:11:24.20 --> 01:11:31.20
That had to have left an impact on you with him as an individual and him as a leader.

835
01:11:31.20 --> 01:11:53.20
It did. And then the next time we got tortured, it was the same thing. He went a lot longer than I did. I went a lot longer than somebody else did.

836
01:11:53.20 --> 01:12:04.20
Because Ken didn't have any experience with any of the other POWs who had been there, he was a very level headed guy and just a great leader.

837
01:12:04.20 --> 01:12:16.20
He was a really good thinker and even some of the things that he did after we came home, like one time he had two squadron commanders when women first started flying in the Air Force.

838
01:12:16.20 --> 01:12:28.20
One of them was in charge of the flying squadron, the other one in charge of the student squadron, and they weren't handling the flying squadron very appropriately with the women there.

839
01:12:28.20 --> 01:12:37.20
And so Ken realized that he needed to do something and he didn't fire them. He switched them.

840
01:12:37.20 --> 01:12:48.20
He put the guy in the student squadron in charge of the flying squadron and the guy in charge of the flying squadron in charge of the student squadron and they both did great and they both got promoted to colonel.

841
01:12:48.20 --> 01:12:57.20
And it was just a brilliant move of how he saw what the situation was and what would be the best solution.

842
01:12:57.20 --> 01:13:10.20
And I think in the POW situation, he was a great example and I didn't have the choice of being put in the ropes or being hung by the ropes like he was in that case.

843
01:13:10.20 --> 01:13:21.20
My situation was death in my case and I think he saw that. I didn't know that they wouldn't kill me, why wouldn't they?

844
01:13:21.20 --> 01:13:33.20
So I think he took all that into account in a really good way but he realized probably at that point that I probably needed to be more confident.

845
01:13:33.20 --> 01:13:46.20
And when leaders are able to help their people believe that they let them know they believe in them, they become more effective and more confident and next time they're going to come through stronger.

846
01:13:46.20 --> 01:13:58.20
So that's a really important leadership point and I've been very fortunate in my life growing up in high school, college days and in the military.

847
01:13:58.20 --> 01:14:09.20
I've had leaders that believed in me. I wouldn't be where I am today if I hadn't had leaders that believed in me and helped me become the person I am today.

848
01:14:09.20 --> 01:14:19.20
So I just think he showed me that and a great example there. And of course later he relieved Lieutenant Colonel Lecomand in that cell.

849
01:14:19.20 --> 01:14:30.20
So he was just very wise, not perfect. I remember after a few months and I finally decided, well, he's not perfect. I can forgive him for that.

850
01:14:30.20 --> 01:14:34.20
But for a while I thought he was just perfect.

851
01:14:34.20 --> 01:14:41.20
Another question we get asked a lot is how can I get this individual to step up into a leadership and start becoming a leader?

852
01:14:41.20 --> 01:14:47.20
Put them in a leadership position. When you put someone in a leadership position, you're telling them, hey, I believe you should be in this leadership position.

853
01:14:47.20 --> 01:14:55.20
I believe that you can lead. And guess what they start doing? They start acting like a leader. Most of the time occasionally you'll get someone that's not ready for you.

854
01:14:55.20 --> 01:15:04.20
They don't have the right attitude yet. But oftentimes you just take someone, a junior individual and say, hey, I want you to run this operation. I want you to run this project.

855
01:15:04.20 --> 01:15:09.20
And they see that you believe in them and that makes them believe in themselves. It's a good move.

856
01:15:09.20 --> 01:15:20.20
You know, speaking of this relief, we'll get into this because I think it's an important and bold move that happens here.

857
01:15:20.20 --> 01:15:29.20
So there's a guy named Lieutenant Colonel Minter. It's actually not his real name. It's a made up name to be gentle, I guess, with the situation.

858
01:15:29.20 --> 01:15:37.20
Well, he had five sons. And I thought that when I wrote that book, I wrote that for his sons. I didn't want to put his name there.

859
01:15:37.20 --> 01:15:44.20
Right. So Lieutenant Colonel Minter was summoned to more interrogations than the rest of us. That seemed natural at first.

860
01:15:44.20 --> 01:15:51.20
As the senior ranking officer, SRO in our room, he was potentially the highest value target for exploitation.

861
01:15:51.20 --> 01:15:57.20
But over time, we realized that Minter's views were not aligned with ours or the policy of our government.

862
01:15:57.20 --> 01:16:04.20
A soldier has the obligation to do his best to uphold the code of conduct, which includes resisting exploitation by the enemy.

863
01:16:04.20 --> 01:16:10.20
What might be acceptable for a civilian back home in our free society is totally out of line for a military person, especially a POW.

864
01:16:10.20 --> 01:16:19.20
One day, Minter came back from an interrogation with pencil and paper and began writing an extensive description of the organization responsibilities of a Marine Air Wing.

865
01:16:19.20 --> 01:16:26.20
We cautioned him that his cooperation was a violation of the code of conduct, but he said he didn't see any problem.

866
01:16:26.20 --> 01:16:37.20
Later, when he was called out of the room for an interrogation, we looked at the paper and saw that it contained information that appeared accurate and of value to the enemy, a clear breach of the code.

867
01:16:37.20 --> 01:16:47.20
Captain Fisher, as the next senior officer in the cell, told Lieutenant Warner and me that he felt compelled to remove Lieutenant Colonel Minter from command.

868
01:16:47.20 --> 01:16:55.20
He asked if we agreed. Is a very serious and risky step for a captain to relieve a Lieutenant Colonel of command?

869
01:16:55.20 --> 01:17:01.20
If competent authority did not support Ken's action, he would likely face a court martial for insubordination.

870
01:17:01.20 --> 01:17:08.20
We also risked court martial for our involvement, but we knew Ken was right, so we gave him our wholehearted support.

871
01:17:08.20 --> 01:17:15.20
When Minter returned to the room, Ken said, you're willing cooperation with the enemy in writing this paper as a violation of the code of conduct.

872
01:17:15.20 --> 01:17:21.20
I am removing you from command and ordering you to destroy that document and cease cooperating with the enemy.

873
01:17:21.20 --> 01:17:26.20
If you disobey these orders, I will personally seek a court martial against you after the war.

874
01:17:26.20 --> 01:17:30.20
That's friggin' awesome.

875
01:17:30.20 --> 01:17:35.20
Minter said he did not believe the code of conduct applied in this case because we were not in a declared war.

876
01:17:35.20 --> 01:17:38.20
In his opinion, everyone was free to do as he saw fit.

877
01:17:38.20 --> 01:17:42.20
That was a shockingly irresponsible attitude for a military officer.

878
01:17:42.20 --> 01:17:46.20
Only a few months previous, he had told friends that he hoped to make general.

879
01:17:46.20 --> 01:17:54.20
Now his comments made him look like a selfish survivor who would forsake his beloved core, his friends, his roommates, and even his country to save his hide.

880
01:17:54.20 --> 01:18:03.20
That evening, Lieutenant Colonel Minter ripped up the document and threw it in the waste bucket, but his behavior over the subsequent years indicated that he never had a change of heart.

881
01:18:03.20 --> 01:18:08.20
So that's a bold move to make.

882
01:18:08.20 --> 01:18:13.20
You're more junior than the senior officer and you say, hey, you're not in charge anymore.

883
01:18:13.20 --> 01:18:14.20
I am.

884
01:18:14.20 --> 01:18:19.20
And by the way, I'm in a court martial after the war if you resist this.

885
01:18:19.20 --> 01:18:28.20
Yeah, it takes courage and believing, you know, it was obvious what was right.

886
01:18:28.20 --> 01:18:32.20
And there was evidence, enough evidence for him to make that decision.

887
01:18:32.20 --> 01:18:35.20
And so he courageously stood up and did it.

888
01:18:35.20 --> 01:18:37.20
And that's the kind of guy Ken was.

889
01:18:37.20 --> 01:18:44.20
So I had this courageous role model living with 24 hours a day, actually for five years.

890
01:18:44.20 --> 01:18:51.20
In fact, we've been home a couple of years and he'd only been married for two and a half years when he was captured.

891
01:18:51.20 --> 01:19:07.20
And his wife, we were his wife and him and my wife and I were at a social event and she came up and says, Lee Ellis, I want you to know I've lived him with Ken Fisher longer than you have.

892
01:19:07.20 --> 01:19:13.20
But he was a great cellmate and a real, he helped me mature.

893
01:19:13.20 --> 01:19:25.20
You know, I needed maturity in lots of different ways and watching him, learning from him helped me to grow into be the person that I needed to be.

894
01:19:25.20 --> 01:19:28.20
And so I got tougher.

895
01:19:28.20 --> 01:19:32.20
I got wiser.

896
01:19:32.20 --> 01:19:44.20
And I would say I don't know to what degree, you know, I would say this, but my own courage grew.

897
01:19:44.20 --> 01:19:54.20
I thought I was pretty courageous, but I think it, I gained courage because I knew what I wanted to do.

898
01:19:54.20 --> 01:20:01.20
I wanted to live up to the code of conduct and be a good American and be faithful to my teammates, do my job.

899
01:20:01.20 --> 01:20:04.20
And so I was willing to take risks.

900
01:20:04.20 --> 01:20:05.20
I was a pretty good risk taker.

901
01:20:05.20 --> 01:20:07.20
I'm in the camp.

902
01:20:07.20 --> 01:20:15.20
I was found it easy to take risks in communicating and things like that because I know I'm good at it.

903
01:20:15.20 --> 01:20:18.20
So I figured I can do it and get away with it.

904
01:20:18.20 --> 01:20:30.20
So they brought this three-page biography questionnaire for us to fill out and we filled it out and put name, rank, service number, date of birth, except for a mentor who filled it in.

905
01:20:30.20 --> 01:20:35.20
And then they hauled the other three of us out to interrogate and threaten us.

906
01:20:35.20 --> 01:20:45.20
It was funny because they had a new interrogator there and he came in and he would say, I don't want to hurt you.

907
01:20:45.20 --> 01:20:47.20
I don't want to bother you, but you're a good person.

908
01:20:47.20 --> 01:20:49.20
You should do this and it'll be all right.

909
01:20:49.20 --> 01:20:52.20
You know, he was a nice guy.

910
01:20:52.20 --> 01:20:53.20
Okay.

911
01:20:53.20 --> 01:20:55.20
And then we say no.

912
01:20:55.20 --> 01:20:57.20
And then the bad guy comes in.

913
01:20:57.20 --> 01:20:59.20
We're going to torture you.

914
01:20:59.20 --> 01:21:03.20
We'll go back and forth for an hour or two and then we didn't fill it in.

915
01:21:03.20 --> 01:21:17.20
So then they put us in handcuffs and tied our feet and put us on our knees up against the wall with our hands over our head, which, you know, no big problem.

916
01:21:17.20 --> 01:21:24.20
But after six or eight hours, you start falling over and then they start coming in and start kicking you and beating you.

917
01:21:24.20 --> 01:21:31.20
And you get back up and after six or eight more hours, you've been up and down and been kicked and beaten and all this.

918
01:21:31.20 --> 01:21:41.20
So finally, after, I don't know, the next day, probably 36 hours, I decided, well, I'm going to give in.

919
01:21:41.20 --> 01:21:43.20
I'm going to give them something.

920
01:21:43.20 --> 01:21:45.20
Ain't going to be nothing, but I'm going to.

921
01:21:45.20 --> 01:21:47.20
And so I told them I would do it.

922
01:21:47.20 --> 01:21:54.20
I filled in the three pages and everything on it was a lie except for my dad's first and last name.

923
01:21:54.20 --> 01:22:02.20
And everything else was just made up, you know, education, money, what everything was just totally made up.

924
01:22:02.20 --> 01:22:09.20
Well, I get back to the room and I wasn't the first one back, but after a while.

925
01:22:09.20 --> 01:22:16.20
But when I did that, when I did that, when I agreed to do it, I laid there and cried.

926
01:22:16.20 --> 01:22:20.20
I was so sad because I was not tough enough to beat him.

927
01:22:20.20 --> 01:22:21.20
I felt so ashamed.

928
01:22:21.20 --> 01:22:29.20
I felt like the most worthless piece of crap that I ever wanted to uniform because I wasn't able to beat him.

929
01:22:29.20 --> 01:22:33.20
My duty was to beat him and I couldn't beat him.

930
01:22:33.20 --> 01:22:43.20
Now, I didn't give him anything, but the fact that I'd filled it in, that was the first time I'd ever really come to grips with the reality that at some point,

931
01:22:43.20 --> 01:22:48.20
you know, you got to fall back to a second round.

932
01:22:48.20 --> 01:22:56.20
Now, when they put the gun to my head earlier, I had, but that was a little different than just being tortured and being painful, uncomfortable,

933
01:22:56.20 --> 01:22:59.20
and being beaten and kicked and all that.

934
01:22:59.20 --> 01:23:02.20
And then when you got back to it, how did Ken Fisher do?

935
01:23:02.20 --> 01:23:09.20
Well, he came back to and he said he had done the same thing, but he was 54 hours longer than me.

936
01:23:09.20 --> 01:23:12.20
He survived, so he was tougher than me.

937
01:23:12.20 --> 01:23:18.20
I'm laughing because that's like, you know, in the SEAL teams, you know, everyone's always competing with everybody else.

938
01:23:18.20 --> 01:23:22.20
And here you guys are competing to see who could take horrible torture longer.

939
01:23:22.20 --> 01:23:23.20
Exactly.

940
01:23:23.20 --> 01:23:34.20
And so as quick as we got communication, though, we found out that everybody had been through it and done the same thing.

941
01:23:34.20 --> 01:23:36.20
Everybody had filled out that biography.

942
01:23:36.20 --> 01:23:40.20
So then I thought, well, I guess I'm not quite as worthless as I thought.

943
01:23:40.20 --> 01:23:42.20
But Ken was good about it, too.

944
01:23:42.20 --> 01:23:49.20
Again, he helped me understand that he didn't go much longer than I did and he had done it, too.

945
01:23:49.20 --> 01:23:51.20
But we didn't give him any information.

946
01:23:51.20 --> 01:23:52.20
Yeah.

947
01:23:55.20 --> 01:24:03.20
Given a little bit more about your life there, for the first two years, the feeling of hunger never left us.

948
01:24:03.20 --> 01:24:09.20
Food was the most popular topic of conversation, especially when it was cold and our bodies needed more calories just to stay warm.

949
01:24:09.20 --> 01:24:16.20
Upon awakening in the winter months, I would realize I'd been dreaming about walking down a cafeteria line, selecting a breakfast of eggs,

950
01:24:16.20 --> 01:24:19.20
bacon, sausage, toast, orange juice, and coffee.

951
01:24:19.20 --> 01:24:26.20
But in reality, our typical meal was a bowl of thin, greasy vegetable soup accompanied by either a cup of rice or an 8-inch baguette of bread.

952
01:24:26.20 --> 01:24:28.20
We joked that the menu had lots of variety.

953
01:24:28.20 --> 01:24:30.20
It changed three times a year.

954
01:24:30.20 --> 01:24:38.20
Since the V cooked outside in big pots, small bugs and white worms would regularly drop into the soup from overhanging trees.

955
01:24:38.20 --> 01:24:44.20
Every August, weevils would hatch in the flour so the bread would be peppered with black buggers.

956
01:24:44.20 --> 01:24:50.20
Having nothing better to do one afternoon, I counted 44 and one cubic inch of bread.

957
01:24:50.20 --> 01:24:56.20
There were too many to pick out, so we just ate them, figuring they were a good source of protein.

958
01:24:56.20 --> 01:25:00.20
Winters in Hanoi were surprisingly cold, with temperatures off into the low 40s.

959
01:25:00.20 --> 01:25:02.20
Fahrenheit sometimes lower.

960
01:25:02.20 --> 01:25:09.20
The chilly air blowing in through our barred open window, covered only with a raton mat, made our unheated cell feel like an ice box.

961
01:25:09.20 --> 01:25:15.20
It was also cold because our meagre rations provided insufficient energy to stay warm through the long nights.

962
01:25:15.20 --> 01:25:22.20
We survived by putting every bit of clothing we owned, two pairs of thin pajamas and a cotton sweater, and wrapping ourselves in our blanket.

963
01:25:22.20 --> 01:25:32.20
For the first two years, we had no socks, so our feet never got warm in the winter.

964
01:25:32.20 --> 01:25:36.20
The POW experience produced severe mental and emotional stress.

965
01:25:36.20 --> 01:25:41.20
Hour after hour, we found ourselves battling an army of oppressive feelings.

966
01:25:41.20 --> 01:25:51.20
From fear about what might happen to us, to anger at our captors for the way they treated us to disappointment for being shot down, to guilt for leaving our families in the lurch and in the dark.

967
01:25:51.20 --> 01:25:55.20
Maintaining a positive mental outlook was crucial to survival.

968
01:25:55.20 --> 01:26:02.20
Military leaders expect life to be difficult, yet they tend to be optimistic about their ability to succeed.

969
01:26:02.20 --> 01:26:11.20
They are trained to make the best of the situation by solving problems instead of stewing about them, and they place a high value on cohesive teamwork.

970
01:26:11.20 --> 01:26:14.20
Fortunately, that's the kind of leadership we had in Hanoi.

971
01:26:14.20 --> 01:26:22.20
A few of our buddies who had more pessimistic temperaments occasionally needed extra measures of encouragement from the rest of us.

972
01:26:22.20 --> 01:26:30.20
In return, they frequently contributed a healthy dose of realism that balanced our optimism with objectivity and discipline.

973
01:26:30.20 --> 01:26:41.20
Vice Admiral James Bond Stockdale insightfully captured the importance of this dynamic tension in what Jim Collins called the Stockdale Paradox.

974
01:26:41.20 --> 01:26:59.20
You must never confuse faith that you will prevail in the end, which you can never afford to lose with the discipline to confront the most brutal facts of your current reality, whatever they might be.

975
01:26:59.20 --> 01:27:15.20
Yeah, that's just a critical way of thinking, right? Having the positive mindset that we can overcome whatever this challenge is, but not being Pollyanna and saying, oh yeah, we'll be fine.

976
01:27:15.20 --> 01:27:20.20
No, there's going to be struggles and we have to face our reality for what it is.

977
01:27:20.20 --> 01:27:23.20
Yeah, I think so. It was very, very important.

978
01:27:23.20 --> 01:27:35.20
You know, I remember, I was shot down November 67. In early 68, I said, you know, there's going to be an Olympics in Mexico City this summer.

979
01:27:35.20 --> 01:27:42.20
We'll be home because I knew that President Johnson really would have to do something with the war to get reelected.

980
01:27:42.20 --> 01:27:45.20
That was my thinking. I didn't know it, but that was my thinking.

981
01:27:45.20 --> 01:27:51.20
I said they will end this war and we'll be home by the summer. I'm going to go to Mexico City and go to the Olympics.

982
01:27:51.20 --> 01:27:57.20
Well, July comes and I moved to Sante and I'm still there.

983
01:27:57.20 --> 01:28:03.20
And they said, well, I've made it seven months. I can make it for another year.

984
01:28:03.20 --> 01:28:13.20
Well, that was one more year. The summer of 69. I said, I can make it two more years, but it was really three, three and a half.

985
01:28:13.20 --> 01:28:21.20
So, you know, the POWs, it became our way of life.

986
01:28:21.20 --> 01:28:30.20
And the fact that we had great leadership, the fact that we did get communication, we communicated covertly,

987
01:28:30.20 --> 01:28:37.20
but we were able to fight as a team, was a common enemy, and to care about each other and look after each other,

988
01:28:37.20 --> 01:28:44.20
we would risk our lives to get to somebody and say, man, we're proud of you. Hang in there. We're leaving without you.

989
01:28:44.20 --> 01:28:56.20
So it was just the leadership, the teamwork and the commitment of our leaders that they got tortured all the time.

990
01:28:56.20 --> 01:29:04.20
And they would do things much worse than we were doing, actually, but they would bounce right back and come back because they did the best they could.

991
01:29:04.20 --> 01:29:10.20
And they bounced back and they put out good policies and they lived by them.

992
01:29:10.20 --> 01:29:22.20
It was an amazing experience. That's why I wrote that book, because I think it's just the principles that we learned and lived by there are good everywhere, you know?

993
01:29:22.20 --> 01:29:24.20
Yeah. No doubt about it.

994
01:29:24.20 --> 01:29:37.20
And here's the thing about it. You couldn't hide, you couldn't pretend because somebody was going to be watching you 24 hours a day, 365 days a year.

995
01:29:37.20 --> 01:29:43.20
There was no way you could hide anything, so you just confessed it all up front.

996
01:29:43.20 --> 01:30:03.20
And I think there's a pride piece in confessing, coming back to the cell and saying, I did feel like that three-page biography, but I didn't tell them anything honest, nothing real, no true facts except for my dad's name.

997
01:30:03.20 --> 01:30:11.20
But it was still painful at times. But I think we realized that that was a way of life.

998
01:30:11.20 --> 01:30:15.20
Yeah, there's you capture some of that in here.

999
01:30:15.20 --> 01:30:24.20
You say, when you are at the mercy of an enemy who has the power to force you to do things against your will, the psychological impact can be unimaginably depressing and debilitating.

1000
01:30:24.20 --> 01:30:29.20
His goal is to break you and you must constantly fight to maintain your self-respect and optimism.

1001
01:30:29.20 --> 01:30:31.20
Most of us did this in two primary ways.

1002
01:30:31.20 --> 01:30:38.20
First, we fought to maintain our belief in ourselves and our competency by resisting the enemy and exercising our autonomy at every opportunity.

1003
01:30:38.20 --> 01:30:47.20
In order to demonstrate that our lives still had worth and we were not just helpless, we had to find ways to get our licks in, often using tricks and subtle acts of rebellions as weapons.

1004
01:30:47.20 --> 01:30:49.20
Subtle acts of rebellions as weapons.

