1092
01:38:21.20 --> 01:38:25.20
It's the one that's going to take care of his team and put the team ahead of himself.

1093
01:38:25.20 --> 01:38:28.20
That's a good seal.

1094
01:38:28.20 --> 01:38:37.20
You give a really crazy and horrific description of, who is it?

1095
01:38:37.20 --> 01:38:41.20
Reisner, Lieutenant Colonel Robbie Reisner.

1096
01:38:41.20 --> 01:38:50.20
And he had like a picture, a picture of his family or something and they, the V wanted it to use it for propaganda.

1097
01:38:50.20 --> 01:38:57.20
He ripped it up and threw it in the bottom of the, of the, of the shit can that you had in the cell.

1098
01:38:57.20 --> 01:39:01.20
And so they are, they want to get this picture.

1099
01:39:01.20 --> 01:39:02.20
So they torture him.

1100
01:39:02.20 --> 01:39:03.20
Here you go.

1101
01:39:03.20 --> 01:39:08.20
They offered to force him to produce the photos that guards severely beat Robbie and put him through rope torture.

1102
01:39:08.20 --> 01:39:14.20
The ropes or pretzels, as it was sometimes called, was a terrifying and brutal method for breaking POWs.

1103
01:39:14.20 --> 01:39:22.20
After the prisoners legs were tied together, his arms were laced tightly behind his back until the elbows touched and the shoulders were virtually pulled out of joint.

1104
01:39:22.20 --> 01:39:29.20
Then the torture would push the bound arms up and over the head while applying pressure with a knee to the victim's back.

1105
01:39:29.20 --> 01:39:37.20
During torture, the circulation is cut off and the limbs go to sleep, but the joint pain continues to increase as the ligaments and muscles tear.

1106
01:39:37.20 --> 01:39:43.20
When the ropes are finally removed, circulation surges back into the dead limbs causing excruciating pain.

1107
01:39:43.20 --> 01:39:57.20
When the V eventually learned what Reisner had done with the photos, they furiously inflicted more torture upon Robbie until he agreed to sign a confession and an apology for committing, quote, grave crimes.

1108
01:39:57.20 --> 01:40:02.20
Under such severe torture, no POW could resist signing these four statements.

1109
01:40:02.20 --> 01:40:12.20
We took some comfort in the fact that they invariably sounded phony because they were dictated by the V using awkward sentence structure and expressions that no American would use.

1110
01:40:12.20 --> 01:40:15.20
Sometimes they were so ridiculous that they made the V look foolish.

1111
01:40:15.20 --> 01:40:22.20
After torture, the guards boarded up the window in Reisner's cell, making it so dark that he couldn't see the walls.

1112
01:40:22.20 --> 01:40:26.20
Robbie had never been afraid of the dark, but he immediately began to have panic attacks.

1113
01:40:26.20 --> 01:40:29.20
In later describing this episode, he said,

1114
01:40:45.20 --> 01:40:48.20
Reisner's only relief was to keep moving and praying.

1115
01:40:48.20 --> 01:40:55.20
He would walk around his cell, often covering as many as 20 miles a day, and do push-ups and sit-ups until he was exhausted enough to fall asleep.

1116
01:40:55.20 --> 01:41:01.20
If he awakened during the night, he had to resume exercising until he was again exhausted enough to sleep.

1117
01:41:01.20 --> 01:41:03.20
It was a maddening existence.

1118
01:41:03.20 --> 01:41:17.20
At times he wanted to scream, but since that would bring more torture, he would hide under his mosquito net, stuff something in his mouth, wrap his blanket around his head, and just holler until the anxiety eased.

1119
01:41:17.20 --> 01:41:22.20
Often he had to talk himself into making it through one more minute and then one more minute.

1120
01:41:22.20 --> 01:41:27.20
As he put it, quote, I literally lived one minute at a time.

1121
01:41:27.20 --> 01:41:32.20
After ten months of darkness, the night finally passed.

1122
01:41:32.20 --> 01:41:39.20
In June 1968, the V removed Robbie into the Golden Nugget section of Little Vegas.

1123
01:41:39.20 --> 01:41:45.20
From our cell about 40 feet away, we heard him moaning and screaming in nightmares throughout the first night.

1124
01:41:45.20 --> 01:41:52.20
The next day when Robbie's shutters were opened, I saw his tired but smiling face for the first time.

1125
01:41:52.20 --> 01:41:57.20
During siesta, while the guards were generally less alert, Reisner and I made contact.

1126
01:41:57.20 --> 01:42:05.20
Over the next few days, he shared his story in basic guidance by writing with his index finger on his open palm one letter of the alphabet at a time.

1127
01:42:05.20 --> 01:42:09.20
It was clear that he had a lot of fight left in him.

1128
01:42:09.20 --> 01:42:15.20
His courage served as an inspiration for the rest of us in the months and years ahead.

1129
01:42:19.20 --> 01:42:27.20
I mean, solitary confinement is one thing, but solitary confinement in complete darkness for ten months.

1130
01:42:27.20 --> 01:42:30.20
Three hundred days.

1131
01:42:30.20 --> 01:42:34.20
And the first time you see him, he's got a smile on his face.

1132
01:42:34.20 --> 01:42:42.20
He looked like an old, old man. He was forty-four or so by that time, but he looked in his sixties.

1133
01:42:42.20 --> 01:42:50.20
He was so wrinkled and pitiful looking, but he smiled and I could tell he was exercising.

1134
01:42:50.20 --> 01:42:56.20
And it was just amazing, you know. He was positive.

1135
01:42:56.20 --> 01:43:05.20
You know, I use, when I'm speaking, I use three of our senior leaders, Reisner, Stockdale and Denton as an example.

1136
01:43:05.20 --> 01:43:13.20
And they were all different personalities. Stockdale was a very introverted, results mission focused guy, stoic.

1137
01:43:13.20 --> 01:43:17.20
Denton was a very outgoing politician kind of guy.

1138
01:43:17.20 --> 01:43:20.20
And Reisner had some of both.

1139
01:43:20.20 --> 01:43:26.20
He was, you know, kind of a mixture of that 20% of the population had some of both.

1140
01:43:26.20 --> 01:43:29.20
But Reisner was just an incredible guy.

1141
01:43:29.20 --> 01:43:39.20
He was so honest and he was the senior ranking officer there, except for when we had some three colonels captured in late 1967,

1142
01:43:39.20 --> 01:43:42.20
but they kept them isolated from us.

1143
01:43:42.20 --> 01:43:45.20
So Reisner was the acting commander of all.

1144
01:43:45.20 --> 01:43:49.20
Denton was, I mean, Stockdale was a senior naval officer.

1145
01:43:49.20 --> 01:43:56.20
But these three guys, they supported each other and they just provided a great example.

1146
01:43:56.20 --> 01:44:05.20
Reisner had incredible ability to bounce back and be positive and do the shameful things he did,

1147
01:44:05.20 --> 01:44:13.20
like take all that torture and then write that confession or whatever it was and then bounce back again.

1148
01:44:13.20 --> 01:44:22.20
And part of it, you know, when you talked about this, taking ownership when you do something

1149
01:44:22.20 --> 01:44:26.20
and the fact that you say, hey, look, this is what I went through and this is what I did.

1150
01:44:26.20 --> 01:44:29.20
And the fact that everyone just kind of was honest with each other.

1151
01:44:29.20 --> 01:44:35.20
You know, I've always told people when you take ownership of something, it's like overcoming an obstacle.

1152
01:44:35.20 --> 01:44:37.20
But once you get on the other side, you feel so much better.

1153
01:44:37.20 --> 01:44:39.20
You know, you get caught in a lie.

1154
01:44:39.20 --> 01:44:40.20
You're making something up.

1155
01:44:40.20 --> 01:44:42.20
You're not telling your parents the truth.

1156
01:44:42.20 --> 01:44:44.20
You're not telling your team the truth about what's going on.

1157
01:44:44.20 --> 01:44:47.20
You feel that heavy burden.

1158
01:44:47.20 --> 01:44:49.20
And the minute you say, hey, listen, everybody, I got to talk to you.

1159
01:44:49.20 --> 01:44:52.20
The plan that I came up with, it's not working and we need to change it.

1160
01:44:52.20 --> 01:44:55.20
Like, it's so liberating to do that.

1161
01:44:55.20 --> 01:45:02.20
And, you know, I often talk about, you know, if you want to get through some trauma that you've been through,

1162
01:45:02.20 --> 01:45:05.20
you got to own it and say, hey, this is what I did.

1163
01:45:05.20 --> 01:45:09.20
Here's what I think I should have done, you know, when you're in combat, things happen in combat.

1164
01:45:09.20 --> 01:45:12.20
You know, a lot of veterans suffer from this.

1165
01:45:12.20 --> 01:45:15.20
You're in combat, things don't go the way you want them to go.

1166
01:45:15.20 --> 01:45:19.20
And you look at it and say, hey, this is what I think I could have done better.

1167
01:45:19.20 --> 01:45:21.20
I should have made this move.

1168
01:45:21.20 --> 01:45:24.20
I should have moved left instead of right or right instead of left or whatever the case may be.

1169
01:45:24.20 --> 01:45:32.20
That, I think, helps you get through these things and it seems like that helps so many people in the camp,

1170
01:45:32.20 --> 01:45:37.20
both when it's happening, right after it happens, and then, you know, I'm sure we'll talk about it,

1171
01:45:37.20 --> 01:45:39.20
the way that you all came back.

1172
01:45:39.20 --> 01:45:43.20
I talked about it with Charlie Plum and William Reader as well.

1173
01:45:43.20 --> 01:45:51.20
Psychologically, for the absolute hell you all had lived through, psychologically, you were actually,

1174
01:45:51.20 --> 01:45:56.20
you actually were, did great in comparison.

1175
01:45:56.20 --> 01:46:03.20
And I think a lot of that, in my assessment as I look at it now, had to do with the fact that you all took ownership of what you did.

1176
01:46:03.20 --> 01:46:06.20
You took ownership of your limitations, right?

1177
01:46:06.20 --> 01:46:09.20
Hey, I can only take so much of this and I signed that paper.

1178
01:46:09.20 --> 01:46:17.20
You know, I think it really did help us to be okay with ourselves.

1179
01:46:17.20 --> 01:46:22.20
It gave us actually more confidence in the long run of dealing with things.

1180
01:46:22.20 --> 01:46:28.20
And the other thing that happened was the fact that we lived together, you couldn't hide things, you know.

1181
01:46:28.20 --> 01:46:31.20
People are going to see you.

1182
01:46:31.20 --> 01:46:34.20
You can, it's going to come out.

1183
01:46:34.20 --> 01:46:43.20
And so we knew that and so therefore it just, we lived totally transparently, completely transparently with each other.

1184
01:46:43.20 --> 01:46:49.20
And so it was just, that made us really so much stronger and healthier.

1185
01:46:49.20 --> 01:46:56.20
It increased our teamwork and our trust for each other because if something went bad, we knew we'd find out right away.

1186
01:46:56.20 --> 01:47:05.20
And of course then being locked up like that, and we could talk about this later, but I want to make sure to mention it now,

1187
01:47:05.20 --> 01:47:14.20
is that because of what the wives and families did back home, they got our torture stopped in late 69 and early 70.

1188
01:47:14.20 --> 01:47:18.20
It changed the policy of the U.S. government, changed the policy of the communist government.

1189
01:47:18.20 --> 01:47:22.20
And so everybody in the world was putting pressure on them about our treatment.

1190
01:47:22.20 --> 01:47:31.20
And so when Ho Chi Minh died in September 69, as soon as they quit celebrating his funeral and the new leaders came in,

1191
01:47:31.20 --> 01:47:35.20
they started rearranging the treatment.

1192
01:47:35.20 --> 01:47:41.20
And so the last three years we were there, it was more live and let live.

1193
01:47:41.20 --> 01:47:49.20
And we had time to decompress and get over our trauma with people who had been through worse than we had.

1194
01:47:49.20 --> 01:47:56.20
So I'm feeling bad about what I went through, but you've been here two years longer and you were tortured with the ropes three times,

1195
01:47:56.20 --> 01:47:59.20
and I didn't go through the ropes.

1196
01:47:59.20 --> 01:48:02.20
And now I can't feel bad about what has happened to me.

1197
01:48:02.20 --> 01:48:04.20
I've got to feel bad about what happened to you.

1198
01:48:04.20 --> 01:48:12.20
And we got so much healthier that POW PTSD is like 4%.

1199
01:48:12.20 --> 01:48:24.20
POW PTSD is much lower than combat veterans because we had people to talk through who had been through worse than we had for years,

1200
01:48:24.20 --> 01:48:27.20
