02:03:45.20 --> 02:03:47.20
You know, Smitty's 93.

1418
02:03:47.20 --> 02:03:49.20
He'll be 94 next April.

1419
02:03:49.20 --> 02:03:51.20
He was a POW for almost eight years.

1420
02:03:51.20 --> 02:03:54.20
I think he was number five or six.

1421
02:03:54.20 --> 02:04:01.20
And his wife had two little girls, five and three, I think, and she was six months pregnant with their son.

1422
02:04:01.20 --> 02:04:03.20
But incredible guy.

1423
02:04:03.20 --> 02:04:10.20
I lived with Smitty for a couple of years and in the same camp with him for probably close to five years.

1424
02:04:10.20 --> 02:04:15.20
But we stayed real close friends and he has a book out, Tap Code, that came out three years ago.

1425
02:04:15.20 --> 02:04:25.20
And I wrote the foreword to it to talk about Smitty and what a great guy he was and what a great example he was for me.

1426
02:04:25.20 --> 02:04:36.20
You mentioned the being at Sante for a while and that's how we originally got connected because I had Terry Butler on who is a Sante raider.

1427
02:04:36.20 --> 02:04:41.20
And he's the one that connected with me with you.

1428
02:04:41.20 --> 02:04:48.20
How, when the Sante raid happened, how did you guys hear about it?

1429
02:04:48.20 --> 02:04:49.20
What did it do to you guys?

1430
02:04:49.20 --> 02:04:51.20
What did you think about it?

1431
02:04:51.20 --> 02:04:59.20
Well, we were, we had moved to this new show place camp because they wanted to show the world how well we're being treated.

1432
02:04:59.20 --> 02:05:00.20
And we heard the bombs going off.

1433
02:05:00.20 --> 02:05:04.20
There was a bomb attack to kind of distract attention.

1434
02:05:04.20 --> 02:05:07.20
And some, we knew something was happening that night.

1435
02:05:07.20 --> 02:05:17.20
And then the next day we could tell about the guards, the way they were acting and the turn keys and guards were like, uh, and then the next morning we moved back to Hanoi.

1436
02:05:17.20 --> 02:05:26.20
They load this all up and they built this camp and put 205, four quadrants of about 50 each in one camp.

1437
02:05:26.20 --> 02:05:30.20
We're in separate quadrants, but we're all in one location.

1438
02:05:30.20 --> 02:05:44.20
So there's 205 of us there and they 48 hours, then 48 hours, they moved all of us back to Hanoi and put us into the cell, the large rooms cells where the Vietnamese had been back for the early years.

1439
02:05:44.20 --> 02:05:46.20
We had never been in there.

1440
02:05:46.20 --> 02:05:54.20
And so we went into these big cells and one of this 1800 square foot cell with 52 guys in there.

1441
02:05:54.20 --> 02:05:55.20
No walls in there.

1442
02:05:55.20 --> 02:05:59.20
Just 1800 open Bay barracks type thing.

1443
02:05:59.20 --> 02:06:02.20
Concrete slab to sleep on, but back to Santé.

1444
02:06:02.20 --> 02:06:08.20
Uh, and hearing it, hearing it, uh, that night we heard it from a show place camp.

1445
02:06:08.20 --> 02:06:10.20
We didn't know what was happening.

1446
02:06:10.20 --> 02:06:26.20
And then because they got scared and moved us back, we started listening and one of the guys, uh, heard on their propaganda, something about that Barry Goldwater had said that we could drop a.

1447
02:06:26.20 --> 02:06:32.20
Men in downtown Hanoi or something like that, and they couldn't stop us or something.

1448
02:06:32.20 --> 02:06:34.20
And that sounded strange.

1449
02:06:34.20 --> 02:06:41.20
And then the next time we really found out was when some of the guys, uh, you shoot down told us.

1450
02:06:41.20 --> 02:06:47.20
And that was a while later, maybe about a year later that we really found out for sure what had happened.

1451
02:06:47.20 --> 02:06:54.20
How exalting was it to be in a room with 50 other people and have all these other people to interact with?

1452
02:06:54.20 --> 02:07:15.20
Well, it was, uh, it was a celebration because we had, I mean, there were some hard parts to it, but they, the good things over overwhelmed the difficult parts because within a couple of weeks, the senior ranking officer looked around and found the one guy who had been a college instructor in the client in the group.

1453
02:07:15.20 --> 02:07:22.20
He'd been recalled on active duty in 1962 and stayed in the Air Force and captain Tom story.

1454
02:07:22.20 --> 02:07:28.20
He said, Tom, I'm putting you in charge of the education program. I want to make it happen.

1455
02:07:28.20 --> 02:07:47.20
Tom found a piece of broken brick tile out in the yard, brought it in and went over on the concrete slab floor over in the corner and started writing down subjects that study math, German, French, Spanish, Russian art and had us go by and put a mark under the ones we want to study.

1456
02:07:47.20 --> 02:08:01.20
So he took a survey and then he recruited teachers. And so within three or four weeks, we had Monday, Wednesday, Friday classes, Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday classes, three hours in the morning, two hours in the afternoon.

1457
02:08:01.20 --> 02:08:14.20
We had toastmasters informal on Tuesday nights on one end of the room, formal on Thursday nights. And we had every kind of class you can think of.

1458
02:08:14.20 --> 02:08:31.20
I was studying Spanish, French and German, teaching beginning French. I took differential calculus from a Naval Academy guy and we were writing problems over in the corner with that piece of broken brick tile and he was teaching me.

1459
02:08:31.20 --> 02:08:43.20
So I mean, we got busy, man. We were so busy. You talk about Paul Galani. Paul Galani and I were in there together and we would speak Spanish, French and German for 10 minutes each.

1460
02:08:43.20 --> 02:09:00.20
For four days a week. We got to the point where we were dreaming in foreign languages. I'd be speaking Spanish to somebody in a foreign language. I didn't have a conversation with them in my dream.

1461
02:09:00.20 --> 02:09:04.20
So that's what our life became.

1462
02:09:04.20 --> 02:09:14.20
Yeah, the amount of effort that you guys made in the section here, you say a number of officers developed a rigorous curriculum and volunteered to teach you the various components of the course.

1463
02:09:14.20 --> 02:09:26.20
This was that you wanted to teach an officer candidate school for the three Air Force enlisted guys. So you guys put together a course of instruction for these enlisted Air Force guys.

1464
02:09:26.20 --> 02:09:34.20
And you say this when the three men returned home, the US Congress approved the program and offered the candidates commissions as second lieutenants in the US Air Force.

1465
02:09:34.20 --> 02:09:41.20
One was so close to retirement, he declined. The other two men accepted their commissions and enjoyed successful careers.

1466
02:09:41.20 --> 02:09:47.20
Unbelievable. You go on to say the lack of books or outside resources did not limit our continuous learning in the POW camps.

1467
02:09:47.20 --> 02:09:56.20
We relied on recall past education and there was a lack of clarity. When there was a lack of clarity on the subject, we tried to get a consensus of the best minds.

1468
02:09:56.20 --> 02:10:05.20
Eventually, many areas were quantified into what we called Hanoi fact, meaning it was accepted as true until we were released and could verify the information.

1469
02:10:05.20 --> 02:10:13.20
The in-house joke was that some men whose education had been slighted before capture and now proudly posed as experts had been totally educated by Hanoi fact.

1470
02:10:13.20 --> 02:10:21.20
Fortunately, it turned out our facts were amazingly accurate. Our investment in developing and development has paid big dividends in a year since.

1471
02:10:21.20 --> 02:10:27.20
I can't believe they took guys just so. Yep. Yeah, you guys learned. We're going to give you guys your commission. Incredible.

1472
02:10:27.20 --> 02:10:41.20
Yep. And you know, similar in the same group, I think it was a group like them. If not the same group, there were four of them, four or five of them were married and about seven or eight of them were bachelors.

1473
02:10:41.20 --> 02:10:48.20
And so the married guys did marriage counseling two days a week. They would teach a marriage course to the single guys.

1474
02:10:48.20 --> 02:10:55.20
And one of the single guys said, well, some of what they said was true, but some of it was probably not the best in the world.

1475
02:10:55.20 --> 02:11:02.20
But you know, they were listening. They were trying to learn about what it's like to be married when we go home.

1476
02:11:02.20 --> 02:11:08.20
I want to go back to the code of conduct here again or to back to the book here. Talk about the code of conduct.

1477
02:11:08.20 --> 02:11:13.20
You say, we found that the code of conduct had to be interpreted in light of specific circumstances.

1478
02:11:13.20 --> 02:11:22.20
How long a person should resist under torture before completing a biography or agreeing to read the propaganda news into a tape recorder to be played over camp radio?

1479
02:11:22.20 --> 02:11:29.20
Under what conditions should we try and escape? How much torture should someone take to avoid meeting with a peace delegation?

1480
02:11:29.20 --> 02:11:39.20
These were not hypothetical issues that a detached executive made in a remote top floor corner office would address for implementation by the rank and file.

1481
02:11:39.20 --> 02:11:46.20
In the POW camps, the decision makers knew they were likely to be the first to follow their own guidance.

1482
02:11:46.20 --> 02:11:53.20
Reisner, Stockdale and Denton made it clear that we were to refuse to participate in propaganda broadcasts.

1483
02:11:53.20 --> 02:12:00.20
But under extreme torture, it was impossible to totally resist. As we learn from the experience of several men who did not come home,

1484
02:12:00.20 --> 02:12:08.20
at some point, mind, body and spirit break, causing loss of rational, coherent thought and the ability to effectively function.

1485
02:12:08.20 --> 02:12:16.20
Therefore, Reisner further clarified this policy by adding that we should quote, take torture indefinitely,

1486
02:12:16.20 --> 02:12:24.20
but stop short of losing life or limb or mental faculties by falling back to a second line of defense.

1487
02:12:24.20 --> 02:12:33.20
Having been pushed beyond his endurance several times, he knew that sometimes temporary submission was the only way to preserve the ability to fight.

1488
02:12:33.20 --> 02:12:44.20
Because some POWs were simply tougher mentally and physically than others, local RSOs had the freedom to interpret resistance policies to suit the circumstances.

1489
02:12:44.20 --> 02:12:47.20
Major Larry Guarino, am I saying that right?

1490
02:12:47.20 --> 02:12:48.20
Guarino.

1491
02:12:48.20 --> 02:12:53.20
Guarino, who heroically stood up to some of the worst treatment during the darkest days of the zoo camp,

1492
02:12:53.20 --> 02:13:00.20
demonstrated wise discernment about how to effectively balance accomplishment of mission and care for the men.

1493
02:13:00.20 --> 02:13:03.20
He said there are wide differences in people.

1494
02:13:03.20 --> 02:13:13.20
A very few men, like Jim Kassler, a major U.S. Air Force, have the stamina and courage to stick to a hard line during severe punishment and continue to hold out.

1495
02:13:13.20 --> 02:13:20.20
Most men, although they want to do a good job, will gamely resist the cruelties, but not for very long.

1496
02:13:20.20 --> 02:13:29.20
Although our leaders were often tortured first and most, they did not pretend to be macho John Wayne heroes.

1497
02:13:29.20 --> 02:13:34.20
On the contrary, they openly shared the pain and despair of their brokenness,

1498
02:13:34.20 --> 02:13:41.20
helping us understand the enemy's tactics and the realities of what was and what was not possible.

1499
02:13:41.20 --> 02:13:50.20
It would have been disastrous for the mission and for their credibility had they been less than totally honest with us about their experiences in the torture chambers.

1500
02:13:50.20 --> 02:14:00.20
Mutual accountability and transparency in the face of a cruel enemy bonded us together tightly.

1501
02:14:00.20 --> 02:14:07.20
An analysis conducted after the war by headquarters U.S. Air Force reflects the sacrifices and commitment made to achieve the mission.

1502
02:14:07.20 --> 02:14:12.20
Nine faithful warriors died before they could return with honor.

1503
02:14:12.20 --> 02:14:20.20
We lost eight brave men due to extreme torture and deprivation in the earlier years and one died of typhoid fever.

1504
02:14:20.20 --> 02:14:24.20
More than 95% of the POWs were tortured.

1505
02:14:24.20 --> 02:14:29.20
Approximately 40% of POWs were in solitary confinement more than six months.

1506
02:14:29.20 --> 02:14:32.20
20% were in solitary for more than a year.

1507
02:14:32.20 --> 02:14:41.20
10% were in solitary for more than two years and several were in solitary more than four years.

1508
02:14:41.20 --> 02:14:47.20
Considering the length of stay in the crowded conditions, our survival record was remarkable.

1509
02:14:47.20 --> 02:14:55.20
Most of us made it back and our mental and emotional state exceeded the predictions of most of the mental health professionals advising the DOD.

1510
02:14:55.20 --> 02:15:03.20
The overall determination and devotion of this group to our mission was impressive.

1511
02:15:03.20 --> 02:15:13.20
Of the nearly 500 POWs in our network, fewer than 10 only 2% willingly cooperated with the enemy.

1512
02:15:13.20 --> 02:15:22.20
And it's again from a leadership perspective, all this leadership was done tapping on walls and setting examples.

1513
02:15:22.20 --> 02:15:27.20
It's just like it's from a leadership perspective is incredible story.

1514
02:15:27.20 --> 02:15:33.20
Well, when you don't have a lot of news and no radio and no TV, you don't get a lot of news.

1515
02:15:33.20 --> 02:15:40.20
And what you get is usually focused on what's happening, how we're resisting.

1516
02:15:40.20 --> 02:15:44.20
And that becomes the headlines.

1517
02:15:44.20 --> 02:15:47.20
And you know where you are.

1518
02:15:47.20 --> 02:15:49.20
You know what's going to happen.

1519
02:15:49.20 --> 02:15:56.20
And you've just got to be able to face up to it and walk that line one step at a time.

1520
02:15:56.20 --> 02:16:14.20
I think that was, every day was an unknown and yet somehow we had to step out every day and be ready for whatever came our way and respond to it in a way that was honorable, that was courageous,

1521
02:16:14.20 --> 02:16:21.20
that we would be willing to stand up to our boss and say, here's what I did and here's why I did it.

1522
02:16:21.20 --> 02:16:36.20
And the amazing thing about this situation, I think one that made it so strong was that the bosses got tortured the most and they had to stand up and say, here's what I did and here's why and here's what happened.

1523
02:16:36.20 --> 02:16:48.20
So the fact that our bosses were so vulnerable, they're very courageous and very tough, but they were vulnerable about sharing what they had been through and what they had done.

1524
02:16:48.20 --> 02:16:56.20
It set an example and it created a culture that was very special.

1525
02:16:56.20 --> 02:17:10.20
Speaking of leadership and you know, as I as we've gone through this book, this is a book about leadership and and a book about, you know, what the human being can come up against.

1526
02:17:10.20 --> 02:17:12.20
But it's absolutely a leadership book.

1527
02:17:12.20 --> 02:17:18.20
I've been, we'll get to some of the leadership a little bit later, but I did want to jump into this point on leadership right now.

1528
02:17:18.20 --> 02:17:28.20
You say this leaders who balance the competing demands of results and relationships are able to push for the achievement of goals while eliciting the best from their people.

1529
02:17:28.20 --> 02:17:43.20
It's as if they have two bank accounts, they make their deposit they make deposits in their results account by consistently accomplishing their goals and they build up capital in their relationship account by caring for their people as individuals of worth.

1530
02:17:43.20 --> 02:17:51.20
In the first instance, they earn credibility with their superiors and in the second they earn loyalty from their followers.

1531
02:17:51.20 --> 02:17:55.20
Occasionally leaders will need to make withdrawals from these bank accounts.

1532
02:17:55.20 --> 02:18:10.20
For example, a leader who is being pressured by unrealistic expectations from above may need to draw on the credibility she's accumulated with her results bank account and say to her superiors, we need to adjust this timetable or burn out our people.

1533
02:18:10.20 --> 02:18:18.20
At other times, she may have to make a withdrawal from the relationship bank account and say to her team, we'll have to work over the weekend to get this job done.

1534
02:18:18.20 --> 02:18:27.20
With regard to balancing mission and people, Admiral Stockdale wisely said, a leader must remember that he is responsible for his charges.

1535
02:18:27.20 --> 02:18:35.20
He must tend to his flock, not only cracking the whip, but washing their feet when they are in need of help.

1536
02:18:35.20 --> 02:18:47.20
Balancing results and relationships is a major leadership challenge. Some leaders are naturally gifted with the head logic and not very good with the heart feelings. Others are the opposite.

1537
02:18:47.20 --> 02:18:52.20
Only about 20% of the population has a natural ability with both.

1538
02:18:52.20 --> 02:19:02.20
Even those with this tightrope walking capability often end up tilting toward a results oriented style because results are typically what get noticed and rewarded.

1539
02:19:02.20 --> 02:19:08.20
If your leadership style is unbalanced, the good news is that you don't have to reinvent yourself.

1540
02:19:08.20 --> 02:19:16.20
To gain better balance, you simply have to develop some of the skills you lack. Simply put, you may either need to toughen up or soften up.

1541
02:19:16.20 --> 02:19:21.20
This may sound artificial, but with practice, your adapted behaviors will feel more comfortable.

1542
02:19:21.20 --> 02:19:30.20
They will never become totally natural, however, so you'll have to consistently and intentionally work at keeping your balance.

1543
02:19:30.20 --> 02:19:34.20
I make a living on that right there.

1544
02:19:34.20 --> 02:19:49.20
I've coached CEOs. I coached a CEO who was a West Point graduate, Army Ranger, had a Harvard MBA, and when I told him, when I confronted him, so to speak, I said, you don't give any positive feedback to your team.

1545
02:19:49.20 --> 02:20:01.20
He had a really good executive team. He said, well, that's just not me. I said, wait a minute, you know better than that.

1546
02:20:01.20 --> 02:20:15.20
I said, your people, they're all different kinds and some of them need a lot more affirmation and feedback than others, but they all need to know that you believe in them, that you care about them, that you see how well they're doing.

1547
02:20:15.20 --> 02:20:37.20
Well, we actually wrote him out a three-centus affirmation for one of the VPs on his team, and I had him stand in front of the mirror and practice smiling to the point that he felt, I said, I want you to go to the point you feel almost ridiculous smiling and energetic and enthusiastic when you say this.

1548
02:20:37.20 --> 02:20:53.20
And he practiced and he did it, and his team performance really went up, but I've coached him for two months, and when I finished his, he said, the last day I was with him, he said, hey, can you stay five minutes after we finish today?

1549
02:20:53.20 --> 02:21:19.20
I said, sure. He said, I got somebody who wants you to meet, so we finished. He jumps up, runs out in the hall, brings in a lady and introduces her as his wife, and she said, well, I just wanted to meet you and say thank you because we have one son, we have one child, one son who's 13 years old, and in the last two or three months, his relationship with our son has totally changed.

1550
02:21:19.20 --> 02:21:28.20
He sits down and asks him questions and listens to him and smiles and encourages him. He said, it's just wonderful. Thank you.

1551
02:21:28.20 --> 02:21:39.20
And I said, well, he did it. He courageously learned how to do things. Well, ten years later, I saw that CEO in a meeting in Atlanta, and I said, how are you doing?

1552
02:21:39.20 --> 02:21:50.20
He said, fine, how's your son doing? Oh, he graduated from college, and he's working at the bank now and says he and I are going to run a half marathon together on Saturday. It just totally changed him.

1553
02:21:50.20 --> 02:22:08.20
Here's a guy who was so results-oriented, he could not even think anything about feelings or relationships or what people's needs were, but once he started letting people know that he cared about them and believed in them, it totally changed his leadership.

1554
02:22:08.20 --> 02:22:14.20
And now he's the CEO of another company, and they think he's the best CEO they ever had.

1555
02:22:14.20 --> 02:22:18.20
Yeah. Yeah, that's awesome.

1556
02:22:18.20 --> 02:22:39.20
And then Leif and I wrote another book, which is called the dichotomy of leadership and what the dichotomy of leadership is about is this. And there's all kinds of different dichotomies we talk about. The first chapter is about, hey, you've got these guys that you love more than anything else in the world, and you're going to send them out on missions that may get them killed.

1557
02:22:39.20 --> 02:22:51.20
And how do you balance that? You got to balance that. And you got to have, you got to care about the men, but you've got to also accomplish the mission. Ultimately, if you don't take care of your men, you're not going to have anyone to execute the mission.

1558
02:22:51.20 --> 02:23:06.20
So you have to prioritize taking care of your team, but you've got the same exact theory here. It was just awesome for me to read it in a different vocabulary, but the exact same message and holds true in any situation.

1559
02:23:06.20 --> 02:23:18.20
And, you know, that chapter or that title, dichotomy of leadership was the last chapter in the book, Extreme Ownership. Because, you know, we said, hey, listen, you're going to be pulled in multiple different directions.

1560
02:23:18.20 --> 02:23:25.20
You got to stay balanced as a leader. That's the thing you got to do. And there's a bunch of categories. You know, you could be a micromanager if you go too far in management.

1561
02:23:25.20 --> 02:23:33.20
You could be too hands off. No one knows what's going on. So communicating. You communicate too much. You communicate too little. So you want to be balanced.

1562
02:23:33.20 --> 02:23:43.20
But we wrote that as one chapter. But as we went out and continue to work with companies, the biggest problem companies have, the biggest problem leaders have would be finding that balance.

1563
02:23:43.20 --> 02:23:54.20
And then like you say in here, you know, people have what they tend towards, right? Some people tend towards, I just need to take care of everyone and they take care of everyone to the point that they don't get anything done.

1564
02:23:54.20 --> 02:23:55.20
Exactly.

1565
02:23:55.20 --> 02:24:04.20
And you have people that tend towards, I'm just going to get the mission done and I don't care what happens. I don't care who's back, I step on to get there. So, uh...

1566
02:24:04.20 --> 02:24:16.20
Yeah, I quoted your book Extreme Ownership a couple of times in my books too, by the way, because I saw your mindset said what I wanted to say and I said, let Jaco say it.

1567
02:24:16.20 --> 02:24:29.20
Yeah, well, in the dichotomy of leadership, we pose all kinds of these opposing forces that you have as a leader. And the opposing force that you phrase very succinctly is results versus relationship.

1568
02:24:29.20 --> 02:24:32.20
Those are two things that are pulling you in opposite directions.

1569
02:24:32.20 --> 02:24:33.20
Mission and people.

1570
02:24:33.20 --> 02:24:34.20
And you got to stay balanced.

1571
02:24:34.20 --> 02:24:47.20
You know, I've been working in assessments of human behavior for 32 years and the one thing I know is that 40% of the population is wired toward results, mission, focus.

1572
02:24:47.20 --> 02:25:00.20
And 40% are wired more towards people, patients, relationship, social focus. And 20% have some of both. But to be a great leader, you have to do both.

1573
02:25:00.20 --> 02:25:10.20
So you're going to have to learn to adapt in certain situations to be either tougher or more affirming and kind.

1574
02:25:10.20 --> 02:25:24.20
The thing that everybody needs to understand, and this goes to the POW, it goes to the fight a pilot world, it goes to everywhere, is that every human being wants to feel valued and important, worthy.

1575
02:25:24.20 --> 02:25:44.20
And when you as a leader are able to let them know that you value them, that you appreciate them, that you believe they have a future, you believe in their future, and that you're going to help them develop, it totally changes their loyalty, their commitment.

1576
02:25:44.20 --> 02:25:48.20
They're going to work harder. They don't want to let you down.

1577
02:25:48.20 --> 02:25:55.20
But that's not easy for results, mission, focus, leaders. It's just not part of their natural mindset.

1578
